# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: llvm-infrastructure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Clang operates in tandem with the LLVM compiler back end and has been a subproject of LLVM 2.6 and later.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] As with LLVM, it is free and open-source software under the Apache 2.0 software license.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Its contributors include Apple, IBM, Microsoft, Google, ARM, Sony, Intel and AMD.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Clang 22 has full support for all published C++ standards up to C++17, implements most features of C++20 and C++23, and has initial support for the C++26 standard.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Since v16.0.0, Clang compiles C++ using the GNU++17 dialect by default, which includes features from the C++17 standard and conforming GNU extensions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] In 2005, Apple Inc. made extensive use of LLVM in several commercial products, including the iOS SDK and Xcode 3.1.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] An OpenGL code compiler for OS X that converts OpenGL calls into more fundamental calls for graphics processing units (GPU) that do not support certain features was one of the first uses of LLVM.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] This enabled Apple to support OpenGL on computers using Intel GMA chipsets, increasing performance on those machines.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] The LLVM project originally intended to use GCC's front end.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] The GCC source code, however, is large and somewhat cumbersome; as one long-time GCC developer put it, referring to LLVM, "Trying to make the hippo dance is not really a lot of fun." Besides, Apple software uses Objective-C, which is a low priority for GCC developers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] As such, GCC does not integrate smoothly into Apple's integrated development environment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Finally, GCC's license agreement, the GNU General Public License (GPL) version 3, requires developers who distribute extensions or modified versions of GCC to make their source code available, but LLVM's permissive software license doesn't require this.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] For these reasons, Apple developed Clang, a new compiler front end which supports C, Objective-C and C++.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] In July 2007, the project received the approval for becoming open-source.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] The combination of Clang and LLVM provides most of the toolchain for replacing the GCC stack.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] One of Clang's main goals is to provide a library-based architecture, so that the compiler could interoperate with other tools that interact with source code, such as integrated development environments (IDE).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] In contrast, GCC works in a compile-link-debug workflow; integrating it with other tools is not always easy.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] For instance, GCC uses a step called *fold* that is key to the overall compile process, which has the side effect of translating the code tree into a form that looks unlike the original source code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] If an error is found during or after the fold step, it can be difficult to translate that back into one location in the original source.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Besides, vendors using the GCC stack within IDEs must use separate tools to index the code, to provide features like syntax highlighting and intelligent code completion.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Clang retains more information during the compiling process than GCC, and preserves the overall form of the original code, making it easier to map errors back into the original source.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Clang's error reports are more detailed, specific, and machine-readable, so IDEs can index the compiler's output.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Modular design of the compiler can offer source code indexing, syntax checking, and other features normally associated with rapid application development systems.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] The parse tree is also more suitable for supporting automated code refactoring, as it directly represents the original source code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Clang compiles only C-like languages, such as C, C++, Objective-C, and Objective-C++.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] In many cases, Clang can replace GCC as needed, with no other effects on the toolchain as a whole.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] It supports most of the commonly used GCC options.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] A Fortran project, Flang was in-progress in 2022.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] However, for other languages, such as Ada, LLVM remains dependent on GCC or another compiler front end.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] The *Flang* project, by Nvidia and The Portland Group, adds Fortran support.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Flang is LLVM's Fortran frontend, often referred to as *LLVM Flang* to differentiate it from *Classic Flang*.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] These are two separate and independent Fortran compilers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] As of October 2023, development versions of Flang were in progress and could be downloaded from the LLVM Project.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Its command-line interface shares many of GCC's flags and options.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Clang implements many GNU language extensions and compiler intrinsics, some of which are purely for compatibility.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] For example, even though Clang implements atomic intrinsics which correspond exactly with C11 atomics, it also implements GCC's `__sync_*` intrinsics for compatibility with GCC and the C++ Standard Library (libstdc++).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Clang also maintains application binary interface (ABI) compatibility with GCC-generated object code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] In practice, Clang is a drop-in replacement for GCC.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Clang's developers aim to reduce memory footprint and increase compiling speed compared to other compilers, such as GCC.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] In October 2007, they report that Clang compiled the Carbon libraries more than twice as fast as GCC, while using about one-sixth GCC's memory and disk space.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] By 2011, Clang seemed to retain this advantage in compiler performance.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] As of mid-2014, Clang still consistently compiles faster than GCC in a mixed compile time and program performance benchmark.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] However, by 2019, Clang is significantly slower at compiling the Linux Kernel than GCC while remaining slightly faster at compiling LLVM.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] While Clang has historically been faster than GCC at compiling, the output quality has lagged behind.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] As of 2014, performance of Clang-compiled programs lagged behind performance of the GCC-compiled program, sometimes by large factors (up to 5.5x), replicating earlier reports of slower performance.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] `libclang` provides a C interface, providing a relatively small API.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] Exposed functionality includes: parsing source code into an AST, loading ASTs, traversing the AST, associating source locations with elements within the AST.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/clang] This table presents only significant steps and releases in Clang history.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In computing, a **compiler** is software that translates computer code written in one programming language (the *source* language) into another language (the *target* language).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The name "compiler" is primarily used for programs that translate source code from a high-level programming language to a low-level programming language (e.g., assembly language, object code, or machine code) to create an executable program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] There are many different types of compilers which produce output in different useful forms.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] A *cross-compiler* produces code for a different central processing unit (CPU) or operating system than the one on which the cross-compiler itself runs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] A *bootstrap compiler* is often a temporary compiler, used for compiling a more permanent or better optimized compiler for a language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Compilers generally implement these phases as modular components, promoting efficient design and correctness of transformations of source input to target output.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Program faults caused by incorrect compiler behavior can be very difficult to track down and work around; therefore, compiler implementers invest significant effort to ensure compiler correctness.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] With respect to making source code runnable, an interpreter provides a similar function as a compiler, but via a different mechanism.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] An interpreter executes code without converting it to machine code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Therefore, some interpreters execute source code while others execute an intermediate form such as bytecode.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] A program compiled to native code tends to run faster than when interpreted, while environments with a bytecode-intermediate-form tends toward intermediate-speed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Alternatively, just-in-time compilation allows for native execution speed with a one-time startup processing time cost.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Low-level programming languages, such as assembly and C, are typically compiled, especially when speed is a significant concern, rather than having cross-platform support.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For such languages, there are more one-to-one correspondences between the source code and the resulting machine code, making it easier for programmers to control the use of hardware.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In theory, any programming language can be used via either a compiler or an interpreter, but in practice, languages tend to be used with only one or the other.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Nonetheless, it is possible to write a compiler for a language that is commonly interpreted.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For example, Common Lisp can be compiled to Java bytecode (and then interpreted by the Java virtual machine), to C code (which can then be compiled again to native machine code), or directly to native code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Theoretical computing concepts developed by scientists, mathematicians, and engineers formed the basis of digital modern computing development during World War II.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Primitive binary languages evolved because digital devices only understand ones and zeros and the circuit patterns in the underlying machine architecture.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In the late 1940s, assembly languages were created to offer a more workable abstraction of the computer architectures.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Limited memory capacity of early computers led to substantial technical challenges when the first compilers were designed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Therefore, the compiling process needed to be divided into several small programs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The front end programs produce the analysis products used by the back end programs to generate target code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] As computer technology provided more resources, compiler designs could align better with the compiling process.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] It is usually more productive for a programmer to use a high-level language, so the development of high-level languages followed naturally from the abilities offered by digital computers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] High-level languages are formal languages that are strictly defined by their syntax and semantics which form the high-level language architecture.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The sentences in a language may be defined by a set of rules called a grammar.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Backus–Naur form (BNF) describes the syntax of "sentences" of a language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] It was developed by John Backus and used for the syntax of Algol 60.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The ideas derive from the context-free grammar concepts by linguist Noam Chomsky.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] "BNF and its extensions have become standard tools for describing the syntax of programming notations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Between 1942 and 1945, Konrad Zuse designed the first (algorithmic) programming language for computers named *Plankalkül* ("Plan Calculus").
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Zuse also envisioned a *Planfertigungsgerät* ("Plan assembly device") to automatically translate the mathematical formulation of a program into machine-readable punched film stock.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] While no implementation occurred until the 1970s, it presented concepts later seen in APL designed by Ken Iverson in the late 1950s.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] APL is a language for mathematical computations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Between 1949 and 1951, Heinz Rutishauser proposed Superplan, a high-level language and automatic translator.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] His ideas were later refined by Friedrich L.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Compiler technology evolved from the need for a strictly defined transformation of the high-level source program into a low-level target program for the digital computer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The compiler could be viewed as a front end to deal with the analysis of the source code and a back end to synthesize the analysis into the target code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Optimization between the front end and back end could produce more efficient target code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Early operating systems and software were written in assembly language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In the 1960s and early 1970s, the use of high-level languages for system programming was still controversial due to resource limitations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] However, several research and industry efforts began the shift toward high-level systems programming languages, for example, BCPL, BLISS, B, and C.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language) designed in 1966 by Martin Richards at the University of Cambridge was originally developed as a compiler writing tool.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Several compilers have been implemented, Richards' book provides insights to the language and its compiler.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] BCPL was not only an influential systems programming language that is still used in research but also provided a basis for the design of B and C languages.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] BLISS (Basic Language for Implementation of System Software) was developed for a Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-10 computer by W.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Wulf's Carnegie Mellon University (CMU) research team.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The CMU team went on to develop BLISS-11 compiler one year later in 1970.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Multics (Multiplexed Information and Computing Service), a time-sharing operating system project, involved MIT, Bell Labs, General Electric (later Honeywell) and was led by Fernando Corbató from MIT.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Multics was written in the PL/I language developed by IBM and IBM User Group.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] IBM's goal was to satisfy business, scientific, and systems programming requirements.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] There were other languages that could have been considered but PL/I offered the most complete solution even though it had not been implemented.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For the first few years of the Multics project, a subset of the language could be compiled to assembly language with the Early PL/I (EPL) compiler by Doug McIlory and Bob Morris from Bell Labs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] EPL supported the project until a boot-strapping compiler for the full PL/I could be developed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Bell Labs left the Multics project in 1969, and developed a system programming language B based on BCPL concepts, written by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Ritchie created a boot-strapping compiler for B and wrote Unics (Uniplexed Information and Computing Service) operating system for a PDP-7 in B.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Bell Labs started the development and expansion of C based on B and BCPL.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The BCPL compiler had been transported to Multics by Bell Labs and BCPL was a preferred language at Bell Labs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Initially, a front-end program to Bell Labs' B compiler was used while a C compiler was developed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In 1971, a new PDP-11 provided the resource to define extensions to B and rewrite the compiler.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] By 1973 the design of C language was essentially complete and the Unix kernel for a PDP-11 was rewritten in C.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Steve Johnson started development of Portable C Compiler (PCC) to support retargeting of C compilers to new machines.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Object-oriented programming (OOP) offered some interesting possibilities for application development and maintenance.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] OOP concepts go further back but were part of LISP and Simula language science.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Bell Labs became interested in OOP with the development of C++.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] C++ was first used in 1980 for systems programming.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The initial design leveraged C language systems programming abilities with Simula concepts.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Object-oriented facilities were added in 1983.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The Cfront program implemented a C++ front-end for C84 language compiler.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In subsequent years several C++ compilers were developed as C++ popularity grew.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In many application domains, the idea of using a higher-level language quickly caught on.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Because of the expanding functionality supported by newer programming languages and the increasing complexity of computer architectures, compilers became more complex.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] DARPA (Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency) sponsored a compiler project with Wulf's CMU research team in 1970.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The Production Quality Compiler-Compiler PQCC design would produce a Production Quality Compiler (PQC) from formal definitions of source language and the target.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] PQCC tried to extend the term compiler-compiler beyond the traditional meaning as a parser generator (e.g., Yacc) without much success.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] PQCC might more properly be referred to as a compiler generator.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] PQCC research into code generation process sought to build a truly automatic compiler-writing system.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The effort discovered and designed the phase structure of the PQC.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The BLISS-11 compiler provided the initial structure.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The phases included analyses (front end), intermediate translation to virtual machine (middle end), and translation to the target (back end).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] TCOL was developed for the PQCC research to handle language specific constructs in the intermediate representation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Variations of TCOL supported various languages.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The PQCC project investigated techniques of automated compiler construction.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The design concepts proved useful in optimizing compilers and compilers for the (since 1995, object-oriented) programming language Ada.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The Ada *STONEMAN* document formalized the program support environment (APSE) along with the kernel (KAPSE) and minimal (MAPSE).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] An Ada interpreter NYU/ED supported development and standardization efforts with the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and the International Standards Organization (ISO).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Initial Ada compiler development by the U.S.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Military Services included the compilers in a complete integrated design environment along the lines of the *STONEMAN* document.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Army and Navy worked on the Ada Language System (ALS) project targeted to DEC/VAX architecture while the Air Force started on the Ada Integrated Environment (AIE) targeted to IBM 370 series.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] While the projects did not provide the desired results, they did contribute to the overall effort on Ada development.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Other Ada compiler efforts got underway in Britain at the University of York and in Germany at the University of Karlsruhe.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] S., Verdix (later acquired by Rational) delivered the Verdix Ada Development System (VADS) to the Army.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] VADS provided a set of development tools including a compiler.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Unix/VADS could be hosted on a variety of Unix platforms such as DEC Ultrix and the Sun 3/60 Solaris targeted to Motorola 68020 in an Army CECOM evaluation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] There were soon many Ada compilers available that passed the Ada Validation tests.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The Free Software Foundation GNU project developed the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) which provides a core capability to support multiple languages and targets.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The Ada version GNAT is one of the most widely used Ada compilers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] GNAT is free but there is also commercial support, for example, AdaCore, was founded in 1994 to provide commercial software solutions for Ada.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] GNAT Pro includes the GNU GCC based GNAT with a tool suite to provide an integrated development environment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] High-level languages continued to drive compiler research and development.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Focus areas included optimization and automatic code generation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Trends in programming languages and development environments influenced compiler technology.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] More compilers became included in language distributions (PERL, Java Development Kit) and as a component of an IDE (VADS, Eclipse, Ada Pro).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The interrelationship and interdependence of technologies grew.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The advent of web services promoted growth of web languages and scripting languages.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Scripts trace back to the early days of Command Line Interfaces (CLI) where the user could enter commands to be executed by the system.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] User Shell concepts developed with languages to write shell programs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Early Windows designs offered a simple batch programming capability.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The conventional transformation of these language used an interpreter.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] While not widely used, Bash and Batch compilers have been written.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] More recently sophisticated interpreted languages became part of the developers tool kit.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Modern scripting languages include PHP, Python, Ruby and Lua.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] (Lua is widely used in game development.) All of these have interpreter and compiler support.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] "When the field of compiling began in the late 50s, its focus was limited to the translation of high-level language programs into machine code ...
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The compiler field is increasingly intertwined with other disciplines including computer architecture, programming languages, formal methods, software engineering, and computer security." The "Compiler Research: The Next 50 Years" article noted the importance of object-oriented languages and Java.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Security and parallel computing were cited among the future research targets.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] A compiler implements a formal transformation from a high-level source program to a low-level target program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Compiler design can define an end-to-end solution or tackle a defined subset that interfaces with other compiling tools e.g., preprocessors, assemblers, linkers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Design requirements include rigorously defined interfaces both internally between compiler components and externally between supporting toolsets.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In the early days, the approach taken to compiler design was directly affected by the complexity of the computer language to be processed, the experience of the person(s) designing it, and the resources available.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Resource limitations led to the need to pass through the source code more than once.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] A compiler for a relatively simple language written by one person might be a single, monolithic piece of software.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] However, as the source language grows in complexity the design may be split into a number of interdependent phases.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Separate phases provide design improvements that focus development on the functions in the compiling process.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Classifying compilers by number of passes has its background in the hardware resource limitations of computers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Compiling involves performing much work and early computers did not have enough memory to contain one program that did all of this work.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] As a result, compilers were split up into smaller programs which each made a pass over the source (or some representation of it) performing some of the required analysis and translations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The ability to compile in a single pass has classically been seen as a benefit because it simplifies the job of writing a compiler and one-pass compilers generally compile source code faster than multi-pass compilers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Thus, partly driven by the resource limits of early systems, many early languages were specifically designed so that they could be compiled in one pass (e.g., Pascal).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In some cases, the design of a language feature may require a compiler to perform more than one pass over the source.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For example, consider a declaration appearing on line 20 of the source which affects the translation of a statement appearing on line 10.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In this case, the first pass needs to gather information about declarations appearing after statements that they affect, with the translation then performed during a subsequent pass.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The disadvantage of compiling in a single pass is that it is not possible to perform many of the sophisticated optimizations needed to generate high quality code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] It can be difficult to count exactly how many passes an optimizing compiler makes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For instance, different phases of optimization may analyse one expression many times but only analyse another expression once.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Splitting a compiler up into small programs is a technique used by researchers interested in producing provably correct compilers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Proving the correctness of a set of small programs often requires less effort than proving the correctness of a larger, single, equivalent program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Regardless of the exact number of phases in the compiler design, the phases can be assigned to one of three stages.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The stages include a front end, a middle end, and a back end.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] This front/middle/back-end approach makes it possible to combine front ends for different languages with back ends for different CPUs while sharing the optimizations of the middle end.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Practical examples of this approach are the GNU Compiler Collection, Clang (LLVM-based C/C++ compiler), and the Amsterdam Compiler Kit, which have multiple front-ends, shared optimizations and multiple back-ends.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The front end analyzes the source code to build an internal representation of the program, called the intermediate representation (IR).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] It also manages the symbol table, a data structure mapping each symbol in the source code to associated information such as location, type and scope.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] While the frontend can be a single monolithic function or program, as in a scannerless parser, it was traditionally implemented and analyzed as several phases, which may execute sequentially or concurrently.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] This method is favored due to its modularity and separation of concerns.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Most commonly, the frontend is broken into three phases: lexical analysis (also known as lexing or scanning), syntax analysis (also known as scanning or parsing), and semantic analysis.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Lexing and parsing comprise the syntactic analysis (word syntax and phrase syntax, respectively), and in simple cases, these modules (the lexer and parser) can be automatically generated from a grammar for the language, though in more complex cases these require manual modification.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The lexical grammar and phrase grammar are usually context-free grammars, which simplifies analysis significantly, with context-sensitivity handled at the semantic analysis phase.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The semantic analysis phase is generally more complex and written by hand, but can be partially or fully automated using attribute grammars.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] These phases themselves can be further broken down: lexing as scanning and evaluating, and parsing as building a concrete syntax tree (CST, parse tree) and then transforming it into an abstract syntax tree (AST, syntax tree).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In some cases additional phases are used, notably *line reconstruction* and *preprocessing,* but these are rare.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The middle end, also known as *optimizer,* performs optimizations on the intermediate representation in order to improve the performance and the quality of the produced machine code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The middle end contains those optimizations that are independent of the CPU architecture being targeted.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Compiler analysis is the prerequisite for any compiler optimization, and they tightly work together.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For example, dependence analysis is crucial for loop transformation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The scope of compiler analysis and optimizations vary greatly; their scope may range from operating within a basic block, to whole procedures, or even the whole program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] There is a trade-off between the granularity of the optimizations and the cost of compilation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For example, peephole optimizations are fast to perform during compilation but only affect a small local fragment of the code, and can be performed independently of the context in which the code fragment appears.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] In contrast, interprocedural optimization requires more compilation time and memory space, but enable optimizations that are only possible by considering the behavior of multiple functions simultaneously.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Interprocedural analysis and optimizations are common in modern commercial compilers from HP, IBM, SGI, Intel, Microsoft, and Sun Microsystems.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The free software GCC was criticized for a long time for lacking powerful interprocedural optimizations, but it is changing in this respect.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Another open source compiler with full analysis and optimization infrastructure is Open64, which is used by many organizations for research and commercial purposes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Due to the extra time and space needed for compiler analysis and optimizations, some compilers skip them by default.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Users have to use compilation options to explicitly tell the compiler which optimizations should be enabled.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The back end is responsible for the CPU architecture specific optimizations and for code generation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Compiler correctness is the branch of software engineering that deals with trying to show that a compiler behaves according to its language specification.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Techniques include developing the compiler using formal methods and using rigorous testing (often called compiler validation) on an existing compiler.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Higher-level programming languages usually appear with a type of translation in mind: either designed as compiled language or interpreted language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] However, in practice there is rarely anything about a language that *requires* it to be exclusively compiled or exclusively interpreted, although it is possible to design languages that rely on re-interpretation at run time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The categorization usually reflects the most popular or widespread implementations of a language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For instance, BASIC is sometimes called an interpreted language, and C a compiled one, despite the existence of BASIC compilers and C interpreters.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Interpretation does not replace compilation completely.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] It only hides it from the user and makes it gradual.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Even though an interpreter can itself be interpreted, a set of directly executed machine instructions is needed somewhere at the bottom of the execution stack (see machine language).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Furthermore, for optimization compilers can contain interpreter functionality, and interpreters may include ahead of time compilation techniques.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For example, where an expression can be executed during compilation and the results inserted into the output program, then it prevents it having to be recalculated each time the program runs, which can greatly speed up the final program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Modern trends toward just-in-time compilation and bytecode interpretation at times blur the traditional categorizations of compilers and interpreters even further.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Meta-tracing is an automated compiler synthesis approach which takes this further and can be used to synthesize a compiler from a language interpreter.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Some language specifications spell out that implementations *must* include a compilation facility; for example, Common Lisp.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] However, there is nothing inherent in the definition of Common Lisp that stops it from being interpreted.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] To implement these features in a compiled language, programs must usually be shipped with a runtime library that includes a version of the compiler itself.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] One classification of compilers is by the platform on which their generated code executes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] A *native* or *hosted* compiler is one whose output is intended to directly run on the same type of computer and operating system that the compiler itself runs on.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The output of a cross compiler is designed to run on a different platform.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Cross compilers are often used when developing software for embedded systems that are not intended to support a software development environment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The output of a compiler that produces code for a virtual machine (VM) may or may not be executed on the same platform as the compiler that produced it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For this reason, such compilers are not usually classified as native or cross compilers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The lower level language that is the target of a compiler may itself be a high-level programming language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] C, viewed by some as a sort of portable assembly language, is frequently the target language of such compilers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] For example, Cfront, the original compiler for C++, used C as its target language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] The C code generated by such a compiler is usually not intended to be readable and maintained by humans, so indent style and creating pretty C intermediate code are ignored.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/compiler] Some of the features of C that make it a good target language include the `#line` directive, which can be generated by the compiler to support debugging of the original source, and the wide platform support available with C compilers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This document is a reference manual for the LLVM assembly language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM is a Static Single Assignment (SSA) based representation that provides type safety, low-level operations, flexibility, and the capability of representing ‘all’ high-level languages cleanly.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It is the common code representation used throughout all phases of the LLVM compilation strategy.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The LLVM code representation is designed to be used in three different forms: as an in-memory compiler IR, as an on-disk bitcode representation (suitable for fast loading by a Just-In-Time compiler), and as a human readable assembly language representation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This allows LLVM to provide a powerful intermediate representation for efficient compiler transformations and analysis, while providing a natural means to debug and visualize the transformations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The three different forms of LLVM are all equivalent.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This document describes the human-readable representation and notation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The LLVM representation aims to be light-weight and low-level while being expressive, typed, and extensible at the same time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It aims to be a “universal IR” of sorts, by being at a low enough level that high-level ideas may be cleanly mapped to it (similar to how microprocessors are “universal IR’s”, allowing many source languages to be mapped to them).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] By providing type information, LLVM can be used as the target of optimizations: for example, through pointer analysis, it can be proven that a C automatic variable is never accessed outside of the current function, allowing it to be promoted to a simple SSA value instead of a memory location.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It is important to note that this document describes ‘well formed’ LLVM assembly language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] There is a difference between what the parser accepts and what is considered ‘well formed’.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] because the definition of `%x` does not dominate all of its uses.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The LLVM infrastructure provides a verification pass that may be used to verify that an LLVM module is well formed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This pass is automatically run by the parser after parsing input assembly and by the optimizer before it outputs bitcode.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The violations pointed out by the verifier pass indicate bugs in transformation passes or input to the parser.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM identifiers come in two basic types: global and local.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global identifiers (functions, global variables) begin with the `'@'` character.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Local identifiers (register names, types) begin with the `'%'` character.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Unnamed values are represented as an unsigned numeric value with their prefix.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Constants, which are described in the section Constants below.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM requires that values start with a prefix for two reasons: Compilers don’t need to worry about name clashes with reserved words, and the set of reserved words may be expanded in the future without penalty.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Additionally, unnamed identifiers allow a compiler to quickly come up with a temporary variable without having to avoid symbol table conflicts.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Reserved words in LLVM are very similar to reserved words in other languages.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] There are keywords for different opcodes (’`add`’, ‘`bitcast`’, ‘`ret`’, etc…), for primitive type names (’`void`’, ‘`i32`’, etc…), and others.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] These reserved words cannot conflict with variable names, because none of them start with a prefix character (`'%'` or `'@'`).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Unnamed temporaries are created when the result of a computation is not assigned to a named value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] By default, unnamed temporaries are numbered sequentially (using a per-function incrementing counter, starting with 0).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] However, when explicitly specifying temporary numbers, it is allowed to skip over numbers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Note that basic blocks and unnamed function parameters are included in this numbering.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For example, if the entry basic block is not given a label name and all function parameters are named, then it will get number 0.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It also shows a convention that we follow in this document.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] When demonstrating instructions, we will follow an instruction with a comment that defines the type and name of value produced.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Strings in LLVM programs are delimited by `"` characters.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Within a string, all bytes are treated literally with the exception of `\` characters, which start escapes, and the first `"` character, which ends the string.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] To represent a `"` character, use `\22`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Newlines do not terminate string constants; strings can span multiple lines.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The interpretation of string constants (e.g., their character encoding) depends on context.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM programs are composed of `Module`’s, each of which is a translation unit of the input programs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Each module consists of functions, global variables, and symbol table entries.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Modules may be combined together with the LLVM linker, which merges function (and global variable) definitions, resolves forward declarations, and merges symbol table entries.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This example is made up of a global variable named “`.str`”, an external declaration of the “`puts`” function, a function definition for “`main`” and named metadata “`foo`”.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] In general, a module is made up of a list of global values (where both functions and global variables are global values).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global values are represented by a pointer to a memory location (in this case, a pointer to an array of char, and a pointer to a function), and have one of the following linkage types.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global values with “`private`” linkage are only directly accessible by objects in the current module.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] In particular, linking code into a module with a private global value may cause the private to be renamed as necessary to avoid collisions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Because the symbol is private to the module, all references can be updated.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This doesn’t show up in any symbol table in the object file.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Similar to private, but the value shows as a local symbol (`STB_LOCAL` in the case of ELF) in the object file.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This corresponds to the notion of the ‘`static`’ keyword in C.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Globals with “`available_externally`” linkage are never emitted into the object file corresponding to the LLVM module.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] From the linker’s perspective, an `available_externally` global is equivalent to an external declaration.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] They exist to allow inlining and other optimizations to take place given knowledge of the definition of the global, which is known to be somewhere outside the module.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Globals with `available_externally` linkage are allowed to be discarded at will, and allow inlining and other optimizations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This linkage type is only allowed on definitions, not declarations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Globals with “`linkonce`” linkage are merged with other globals of the same name when linkage occurs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This can be used to implement some forms of inline functions, templates, or other code which must be generated in each translation unit that uses it, but where the body may be overridden with a more definitive definition later.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Unreferenced `linkonce` globals are allowed to be discarded.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Note that `linkonce` linkage does not actually allow the optimizer to inline the body of this function into callers because it doesn’t know if this definition of the function is the definitive definition within the program or whether it will be overridden by a stronger definition.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] To enable inlining and other optimizations, use “`linkonce_odr`” linkage.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] “`weak`” linkage has the same merging semantics as `linkonce` linkage, except that unreferenced globals with `weak` linkage may not be discarded.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This is used for globals that are declared “weak” in C source code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] “`common`” linkage is most similar to “`weak`” linkage, but they are used for tentative definitions in C, such as “`int X;`” at global scope.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Symbols with “`common`” linkage are merged in the same way as `weak symbols`, and they may not be deleted if unreferenced.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] `common` symbols may not have an explicit section, must have a zero initializer, and may not be marked ‘constant’.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Functions and aliases may not have common linkage.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] “`appending`” linkage may only be applied to global variables of pointer to array type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] When two global variables with appending linkage are linked together, the two global arrays are appended together.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This is the LLVM, typesafe, equivalent of having the system linker append together “sections” with identical names when `.o` files are linked.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Unfortunately this doesn’t correspond to any feature in `.o` files, so it can only be used for variables like `llvm.global_ctors` which llvm interprets specially.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The semantics of this linkage follow the ELF object file model: the symbol is weak until linked, if not linked, the symbol becomes null instead of being an undefined reference.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The `odr` suffix indicates that all globals defined with the given name are equivalent, along the lines of the C++ “one definition rule” (“ODR”).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Informally, this means we can inline functions and fold loads of constants.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Formally, use the following definition: when an `odr` function is called, one of the definitions is non-deterministically chosen to run.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For `odr` variables, if any byte in the value is not equal in all initializers, that byte is a poison value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For aliases and ifuncs, apply the rule for the underlying function or variable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] These linkage types are otherwise the same as their non-`odr` versions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If none of the above identifiers are used, the global is externally visible, meaning that it participates in linkage and can be used to resolve external symbol references.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It is illegal for a global variable or function *declaration* to have any linkage type other than `external` or `extern_weak`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM functions, calls and invokes can all have an optional calling convention specified for the call.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The calling convention of any pair of dynamic caller/callee must match, or the behavior of the program is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention (the default if no other calling convention is specified) matches the target C calling conventions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention supports varargs function calls and tolerates some mismatch in the declared prototype and implemented declaration of the function (as does normal C).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention attempts to make calls as fast as possible (e.g., by passing things in registers).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention allows the target to use whatever tricks it wants to produce fast code for the target, without having to conform to an externally specified ABI (Application Binary Interface).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Targets may use different implementations according to different features.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] In this case, a TTI interface `useFastCCForInternalCall` must return false when any caller functions and the callee belong to different implementations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Tail calls can only be optimized when this, the tailcc, the GHC or the HiPE convention is used.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention does not support varargs and requires the prototype of all callees to exactly match the prototype of the function definition.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention attempts to make code in the caller as efficient as possible under the assumption that the call is not commonly executed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] As such, these calls often preserve all registers so that the call does not break any live ranges in the caller side.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Furthermore the inliner doesn’t consider such function calls for inlining.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention has been implemented specifically for use by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It passes everything in registers, going to extremes to achieve this by disabling callee save registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention should not be used lightly but only for specific situations such as an alternative to the *register pinning* performance technique often used when implementing functional programming languages.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] At the moment only X86, AArch64, and RISCV support this convention.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention supports tail call optimization but requires both the caller and callee to use it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention has been implemented specifically for use by the High-Performance Erlang (HiPE) compiler, *the* native code compiler of the Ericsson’s Open Source Erlang/OTP system.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It uses more registers for argument passing than the ordinary C calling convention and defines no callee-saved registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The calling convention properly supports tail call optimization but requires that both the caller and the callee use it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It uses a *register pinning* mechanism, similar to GHC’s convention, for keeping frequently accessed runtime components pinned to specific hardware registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] At the moment only X86 supports this convention (both 32 and 64 bit).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This is a special convention that supports patching an arbitrary code sequence in place of a call site.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This convention forces the call arguments into registers but allows them to be dynamically allocated.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This can currently only be used with calls to `llvm.experimental.patchpoint` because only this intrinsic records the location of its arguments in a side table.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] See Stack maps and patch points in LLVM.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention attempts to make the code in the caller as unintrusive as possible.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This convention behaves identically to the *C* calling convention on how arguments and return values are passed, but it uses a different set of caller/callee-saved registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This alleviates the burden of saving and recovering a large register set before and after the call in the caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If the arguments are passed in callee-saved registers, then they will be preserved by the callee across the call.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This doesn’t apply for values returned in callee-saved registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The idea behind this convention is to support calls to runtime functions that have a hot path and a cold path.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The hot path is usually a small piece of code that doesn’t use many registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The cold path might need to call out to another function and therefore only needs to preserve the caller-saved registers, which haven’t already been saved by the caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The *PreserveMost* calling convention is very similar to the *cold* calling convention in terms of caller/callee-saved registers, but they are used for different types of function calls.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] *coldcc* is for function calls that are rarely executed, whereas *preserve_mostcc* function calls are intended to be on the hot path and definitely executed a lot.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Furthermore *preserve_mostcc* doesn’t prevent the inliner from inlining the function call.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention will be used by a future version of the Objective-C runtime and should therefore still be considered experimental at this time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Although this convention was created to optimize certain runtime calls to the Objective-C runtime, it is not limited to this runtime and might be used by other runtimes in the future too.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The current implementation only supports X86-64, but the intention is to support more architectures in the future.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention attempts to make the code in the caller even less intrusive than the *PreserveMost* calling convention.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention also behaves identically to the *C* calling convention on how arguments and return values are passed, but it uses a different set of caller/callee-saved registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This removes the burden of saving and recovering a large register set before and after the call in the caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The idea behind this convention is to support calls to runtime functions that don’t need to call out to any other functions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention, like the *PreserveMost* calling convention, will be used by a future version of the Objective-C runtime and should be considered experimental at this time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention doesn’t preserve any general registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] So all general registers are caller saved registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It also uses all general registers to pass arguments.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This attribute doesn’t impact non-general purpose registers (e.g., floating point registers, on X86 XMMs/YMMs).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Non-general purpose registers still follow the standard C calling convention.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Currently it is for x86_64, AArch64 and LoongArch only.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Clang generates an access function to access C++-style Thread Local Storage (TLS).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The access function generally has an entry block, an exit block and an initialization block that is run at the first time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The entry and exit blocks can access a few TLS IR variables, each access will be lowered to a platform-specific sequence.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention aims to minimize overhead in the caller by preserving as many registers as possible (all the registers that are preserved on the fast path, composed of the entry and exit blocks).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention behaves identically to the *C* calling convention on how arguments and return values are passed, but it uses a different set of caller/callee-saved registers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Given that each platform has its own lowering sequence, hence its own set of preserved registers, we can’t use the existing *PreserveMost*.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention ensures that calls in tail position will always be tail call optimized.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention is equivalent to fastcc, except for an additional guarantee that tail calls will be produced whenever possible.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Tail calls can only be optimized when this, the fastcc, the GHC or the HiPE convention is used.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention is like `swiftcc` in most respects, but also the callee pops the argument area of the stack so that mandatory tail calls are possible as in `tailcc`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This calling convention is used for the Control Flow Guard check function, calls to which can be inserted before indirect calls to check that the call target is a valid function address.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The check function has no return value, but it will trigger an OS-level error if the address is not a valid target.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The set of registers preserved by the check function, and the register containing the target address are architecture-specific.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Any calling convention may be specified by number, allowing target-specific calling conventions to be used.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Target-specific calling conventions start at 64.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] More calling conventions can be added/defined on an as-needed basis, to support Pascal conventions or any other well-known target-independent convention.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] On targets that use the ELF object file format, default visibility means that the declaration is visible to other modules and, in shared libraries, means that the declared entity may be overridden.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] On Darwin, default visibility means that the declaration is visible to other modules.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] On XCOFF, default visibility means no explicit visibility bit will be set and whether the symbol is visible (i.e “exported”) to other modules depends primarily on export lists provided to the linker.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Default visibility corresponds to “external linkage” in the language.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Two declarations of an object with hidden visibility refer to the same object if they are in the same shared object.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Usually, hidden visibility indicates that the symbol will not be placed into the dynamic symbol table, so no other module (executable or shared library) can reference it directly.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] On ELF, protected visibility indicates that the symbol will be placed in the dynamic symbol table, but that references within the defining module will bind to the local symbol.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] That is, the symbol cannot be overridden by another module.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] A symbol with `internal` or `private` linkage must have `default` visibility.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] “`dllimport`” causes the compiler to reference a function or variable via a global pointer to a pointer that is set up by the DLL exporting the symbol.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] On Microsoft Windows targets, the pointer name is formed by combining `__imp_` and the function or variable name.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] On Microsoft Windows targets, “`dllexport`” causes the compiler to provide a global pointer to a pointer in a DLL, so that it can be referenced with the `dllimport` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The pointer name is formed by combining `__imp_` and the function or variable name.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] On XCOFF targets, `dllexport` indicates that the symbol will be made visible to other modules using “exported” visibility and thus placed by the linker in the loader section symbol table.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Since this storage class exists for defining a DLL interface, the compiler, assembler and linker know it is externally referenced and must refrain from deleting the symbol.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] A symbol with `internal` or `private` linkage cannot have a DLL storage class.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] A variable may be defined as `thread_local`, which means that it will not be shared by threads (each thread will have a separate copy of the variable).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Not all targets support thread-local variables.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For variables that are only used within the current shared library.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For variables in modules that will not be loaded dynamically.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For variables defined in the executable and only used within it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If no explicit model is given, the “general dynamic” model is used.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The models correspond to the ELF TLS models; see ELF Handling For Thread-Local Storage for more information on under which circumstances the different models may be used.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The target may choose a different TLS model if the specified model is not supported, or if a better choice of model can be made.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] A model can also be specified in an alias, but then it only governs how the alias is accessed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] It will not have any effect on the aliasee.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For platforms without linker support of ELF TLS model, the `-femulated-tls` flag can be used to generate GCC-compatible emulated TLS code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global variables, functions and aliases may have an optional runtime preemption specifier.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If a preemption specifier isn’t given explicitly, then a symbol is assumed to be `dso_preemptable`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Indicates that the function or variable may be replaced by a symbol from outside the linkage unit at runtime.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The compiler may assume that a function or variable marked as `dso_local` will resolve to a symbol within the same linkage unit.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Direct access will be generated even if the definition is not within this compilation unit.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM IR allows you to specify both “identified” and “literal” structure types.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Literal types are uniqued structurally, but identified types are never uniqued.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] An opaque structural type can also be used to forward declare a type that is not yet available.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Prior to the LLVM 3.0 release, identified types were structurally uniqued.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Only literal types are uniqued in recent versions of LLVM.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Note: non-integral pointer types are a work in progress, and they should be considered experimental at this time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For most targets, the pointer representation is a direct mapping from the bitwise representation to the address of the underlying memory location.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Such pointers are considered “integral”, and any pointers where the representation is not just an integer address are called “non-integral”.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] These properties (or combinations thereof) can be applied to pointers via the datalayout string.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The exact implications of these properties are target-specific.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The following subsections describe the IR semantics and restrictions to optimization passes for each of these properties.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Pointers in this address space have a bitwise representation that not only has address bits, but also some other target-specific metadata.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] In most cases pointers with non-address bits behave exactly the same as integral pointers, the only difference is that it is not possible to create a pointer just from an address unless all the non-address bits are also recreated correctly in a target-specific way.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] An example of pointers with non-address bits are the AMDGPU buffer descriptors which are 160 bits: a 128-bit fat pointer and a 32-bit offset.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Similarly, CHERI capabilities contain a 32- or 64-bit address as well as the same number of metadata bits, but unlike the AMDGPU buffer descriptors they have external state in addition to non-address bits.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Pointers in this address space have an *unspecified* bitwise representation (i.e., not backed by a fixed integer).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The bitwise pattern of such pointers is allowed to change in a target-specific way.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For example, this could be a pointer type used with copying garbage collection where the garbage collector could update the pointer at any time in the collection sweep.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] `inttoptr` and `ptrtoint` instructions have the same semantics as for integral (i.e., normal) pointers in that they convert integers to and from corresponding pointer types, but there are additional implications to be aware of.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For “unstable” pointer representations, the bit-representation of the pointer may not be stable, so two identical casts of the same operand may or may not return the same value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Said differently, the conversion to or from the “unstable” pointer type depends on environmental state in an implementation defined manner.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If the frontend wishes to observe a *particular* value following a cast, the generated IR must fence with the underlying environment in an implementation defined manner.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] From the perspective of the optimizer, `inttoptr` and `ptrtoint` for “unstable” pointer types are analogous to ones on integral types with one key exception: the optimizer may not, in general, insert new dynamic occurrences of such casts.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If a new cast is inserted, the optimizer would need to either ensure that a) all possible values are valid, or b) appropriate fencing is inserted.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Since the appropriate fencing is implementation defined, the optimizer can’t do the latter.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The former is challenging as many commonly expected properties, such as `ptrtoint(v)-ptrtoint(v) == 0`, don’t hold for “unstable” pointer types.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Similar restrictions apply to intrinsics that might examine the pointer bits, such as llvm.ptrmask.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The alignment information provided by the frontend for an “unstable” pointer (typically using attributes or metadata) must be valid for every possible representation of the pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] A further special case of non-integral pointers is ones that include external state (such as bounds information or a type tag) with a target-defined size.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] An example of such a type is a CHERI capability, where there is an additional validity bit that is part of all pointer-typed registers, but is located in memory at an implementation-defined address separate from the pointer itself.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Another example would be a fat-pointer scheme where pointers remain plain integers, but the associated bounds are stored in an out-of-band table.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Unless also marked as “unstable”, the bit-wise representation of pointers with external state is stable and `ptrtoint(x)` always yields a deterministic value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This means transformation passes are still permitted to insert new `ptrtoint` instructions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The `inttoptr` instruction does not recreate the external state and therefore it is target dependent whether it can be used to create a dereferenceable pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] In general passes should assume that the result of such an `inttoptr` is not dereferenceable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For example, on CHERI targets an `inttoptr` will yield a capability with the external state (the validity tag bit) set to zero, which will cause any dereference to trap.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The `ptrtoint` instruction also only returns the “in-band” state and omits all external state.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] When a `store ptr addrspace(N) %p, ptr @dst` of such a non-integral pointer is performed, the external metadata is also stored to an implementation-defined location.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Similarly, a `%val = load ptr addrspace(N), ptr @dst` will fetch the external metadata and make it available for all uses of `%val`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Similarly, the `llvm.memcpy` and `llvm.memmove` intrinsics also transfer the external state.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This is essential to allow frontends to efficiently emit copies of structures containing such pointers, since expanding all these copies as individual loads and stores would affect compilation speed and inhibit optimizations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Notionally, these external bits are part of the pointer, but since `inttoptr` / ptrtoint` only operate on the “in-band” bits of the pointer and the external bits are not explicitly exposed, they are not included in the size specified in the datalayout string.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] When a pointer type has external state, all roundtrips via memory must be performed as loads and stores of the correct type since stores of other types may not propagate the external data.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Therefore it is not legal to convert an existing load/store (or a `llvm.memcpy` / `llvm.memmove` intrinsic) of pointer types with external state to a load/store of an integer or byte type with the same bitwidth, as that may drop the external state.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global variables define regions of memory allocated at compilation time instead of run-time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global variable definitions must be initialized with a sized value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global variables in other translation units can also be declared, in which case they don’t have an initializer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global variables can optionally specify a linkage type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Either global variable definitions or declarations may have an explicit section to be placed in and may have an optional explicit alignment specified.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If there is a mismatch between the explicit or inferred section information for the variable declaration and its definition, the resulting behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] A variable may be defined as a global `constant`, which indicates that the contents of the variable will **never** be modified (enabling better optimization, allowing the global data to be placed in the read-only section of an executable, etc).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Note that variables that need runtime initialization cannot be marked `constant` as there is a store to the variable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM explicitly allows *declarations* of global variables to be marked constant, even if the final definition of the global is not.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This capability can be used to enable slightly better optimization of the program, but requires the language definition to guarantee that optimizations based on the ‘constantness’ are valid for the translation units that do not include the definition.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] As SSA values, global variables define pointer values that are in scope for (i.e., they dominate) all basic blocks in the program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global variables always define a pointer to their “content” type because they describe a region of memory, and all allocated object in LLVM are accessed through pointers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Global variables can be marked with `unnamed_addr` which indicates that the address is not significant, only the content.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Constants marked like this can be merged with other constants if they have the same initializer, and can also be duplicated.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Note that a constant with significant address *can* be merged with a `unnamed_addr` constant, the result being a constant whose address is significant.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Constant duplication currently makes it unsound to compare pointers if either may be `unnamed_addr`, because each reference to the global in the IR may return a different pointer, and optimization passes may create additional references.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If the `local_unnamed_addr` attribute is given, the address is known to not be significant within the module.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] A global variable may be declared to reside in a target-specific numbered address space.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For targets that support them, address spaces may affect how optimizations are performed and/or what target instructions are used to access the variable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The address space qualifier must precede any other attributes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM allows an explicit section to be specified for globals.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If the target supports it, it will emit globals to the section specified.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Additionally, the global can be placed in a comdat if the target has the necessary support.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] External declarations may have an explicit section specified.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Section information is retained in LLVM IR for targets that make use of this information.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Attaching section information to an external declaration is an assertion that its definition is located in the specified section.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If the definition is located in a different section, the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM allows an explicit code model to be specified for globals.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If the target supports it, it will emit globals in the code model specified, overriding the code model used to compile the translation unit.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The allowed values are “tiny”, “small”, “kernel”, “medium”, “large”.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This may be extended in the future to specify global data layout that doesn’t cleanly fit into a specific code model.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] By default, global initializers are optimized by assuming that global variables defined within the module are not modified from their initial values before the start of the global initializer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This is true even for variables potentially accessible from outside the module, including those with external linkage or appearing in `@llvm.used` or dllexported variables.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] This assumption may be suppressed by marking the variable with `externally_initialized`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] An explicit alignment may be specified for a global, which must be a power of 2.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If not present, or if the alignment is set to zero, the alignment of the global is set by the target to whatever it feels convenient.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If an explicit alignment is specified, the global is forced to have exactly that alignment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Targets and optimizers are not allowed to over-align the global if the global has an assigned section.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] In this case, the extra alignment could be observable: for example, code could assume that the globals are densely packed in their section and try to iterate over them as an array, alignment padding would break this iteration.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For TLS variables, the module flag `MaxTLSAlign`, if present, limits the alignment to the given value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Optimizers are not allowed to impose a stronger alignment on these variables.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Globals can also have a DLL storage class, an optional runtime preemption specifier, an optional global attributes and an optional list of attached metadata.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Variables and aliases can have a Thread Local Storage Model.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Globals cannot be or contain Scalable vectors because their size is unknown at compile time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] They are allowed in structs to facilitate intrinsics returning multiple values.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Generally, structs containing scalable vectors are not considered “sized” and cannot be used in loads, stores, allocas, or GEPs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The only exception to this rule is for structs that contain scalable vectors of the same type (e.g., `{<vscale x 2 x i32>, <vscale x 2 x i32>}` contains the same type while `{<vscale x 2 x i32>, <vscale x 2 x i64>}` doesn’t).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] These kinds of structs (we may call them homogeneous scalable vector structs) are considered sized and can be used in loads, stores, allocas, but not GEPs.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Globals with `toc-data` attribute set are stored in TOC of XCOFF.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Their alignments are not larger than that of a TOC entry.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Optimizations should not increase their alignments to mitigate TOC overflow.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] A function definition contains a list of basic blocks, forming the CFG (Control Flow Graph) for the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Each basic block may optionally start with a label (giving the basic block a symbol table entry), contains a list of instructions and debug records, and ends with a terminator instruction (such as a branch or function return).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If an explicit label name is not provided, a block is assigned an implicit numbered label, using the next value from the same counter as used for unnamed temporaries (see above).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] For example, if a function entry block does not have an explicit label, it will be assigned label “%0”, then the first unnamed temporary in that block will be “%1”, etc.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If a numeric label is explicitly specified, it must match the numeric label that would be used implicitly.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The first basic block in a function is special in two ways: it is immediately executed on entrance to the function, and it is not allowed to have predecessor basic blocks (i.e., there can not be any branches to the entry block of a function).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Because the block can have no predecessors, it also cannot have any PHI nodes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] LLVM allows an explicit section to be specified for functions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If the target supports it, it will emit functions to the section specified.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Additionally, the function can be placed in a COMDAT.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] An explicit minimum alignment (`align`) may be specified for a function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If not present, or if the alignment is set to zero, the alignment of the function is set according to the preferred alignment rules described below.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If an explicit minimum alignment is specified, the function is forced to have at least that much alignment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] An explicit preferred alignment (`prefalign`) may also be specified for a function (definitions only, and must be a power of 2).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If a function does not have a preferred alignment attribute, the preferred alignment is determined in a target-specific way.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] The preferred alignment, if provided, is treated as a hint; the final alignment of the function will generally be set to a value somewhere between the minimum alignment and the preferred alignment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If the `unnamed_addr` attribute is given, the address is known to not be significant and two identical functions can be merged.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] If an explicit address space is not given, it will default to the program address space from the datalayout string.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] Aliases, unlike function or variables, don’t create any new data.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p01] They are just a new symbol and metadata for an existing position.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Aliases have a name and an aliasee that is either a global value or a constant expression.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Aliases may have an optional linkage type, an optional runtime preemption specifier, an optional visibility style, an optional DLL storage class and an optional tls model.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The linkage must be one of `private`, `internal`, `linkonce`, `weak`, `linkonce_odr`, `weak_odr`, `external`, `available_externally`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that some system linkers might not correctly handle dropping a weak symbol that is aliased.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Aliases that are not `unnamed_addr` are guaranteed to have the same address as the aliasee expression.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] `unnamed_addr` ones are only guaranteed to point to the same content.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] IFuncs, like aliases, don’t create any new data or func.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] They are just a new symbol that is resolved at runtime by calling a resolver function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] On ELF platforms, IFuncs are resolved by the dynamic linker at load time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] On Mach-O platforms, they are lowered in terms of `.symbol_resolver` functions, which lazily resolve the callee the first time they are called.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] IFunc may have an optional linkage type, an optional visibility style, an option partition, and an optional list of attached metadata.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Comdat IR provides access to object file COMDAT/section group functionality which represents interrelated sections.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Comdats have a name which represents the COMDAT key and a selection kind to provide input on how the linker deduplicates comdats with the same key in two different object files.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A comdat must be included or omitted as a unit.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Discarding the whole comdat is allowed but discarding a subset is not.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A global object may be a member of at most one comdat.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Aliases are placed in the same COMDAT that their aliasee computes to, if any.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For selection kinds other than `nodeduplicate`, only one of the duplicate comdats may be retained by the linker and the members of the remaining comdats must be discarded.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The linker may choose any COMDAT key, the choice is arbitrary.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The linker may choose any COMDAT key but the sections must contain the same data.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The linker will choose the section containing the largest COMDAT key.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The linker may choose any COMDAT key but the sections must contain the same amount of data.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] There are some restrictions on the properties of the global object.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] It, or an alias to it, must have the same name as the COMDAT group when targeting COFF.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The contents and size of this object may be used during link-time to determine which COMDAT groups get selected depending on the selection kind.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Because the name of the object must match the name of the COMDAT group, the linkage of the global object must not be local; local symbols can get renamed if a collision occurs in the symbol table.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The combined use of COMDATS and section attributes may yield surprising results.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] From the object file perspective, this requires the creation of two sections with the same name.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is necessary because both globals belong to different COMDAT groups and COMDATs, at the object file level, are represented by sections.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that certain IR constructs like global variables and functions may create COMDATs in the object file in addition to any which are specified using COMDAT IR.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This arises when the code generator is configured to emit globals in individual sections (e.g., when *-data-sections* or *-function-sections* is supplied to *llc*).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The return type and each parameter of a function type may have a set of *parameter attributes* associated with them.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Parameter attributes are used to communicate additional information about the result or parameters of a function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Parameter attributes are considered to be part of the function, not of the function type, so functions with different parameter attributes can have the same function type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Parameter attributes can be placed both on function declarations/definitions, and at call-sites.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Parameter attributes are either simple keywords or strings that follow the specified type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Multiple parameter attributes, when required, are separated by spaces.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that any attributes for the function result (`nonnull`, `signext`) come before the result type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Parameter attributes can be broadly separated into two kinds: ABI attributes that affect how values are passed to/from functions, like `zeroext`, `inreg`, `byval`, or `sret`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] And optimization attributes, which provide additional optimization guarantees, like `noalias`, `nonnull` and `dereferenceable`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] ABI attributes must be specified *both* at the function declaration/definition and call-site, otherwise the behavior may be undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] ABI attributes cannot be safely dropped.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Optimization attributes do not have to match between call-site and function: The intersection of their implied semantics applies.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Optimization attributes can also be freely dropped.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If an integer argument to a function is not marked signext/zeroext/noext, the kind of extension used is target-specific.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Some targets depend for correctness on the kind of extension to be explicitly specified.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates to the code generator that the parameter or return value should be zero-extended to the extent required by the target’s ABI by the caller (for a parameter) or the callee (for a return value).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates to the code generator that the parameter or return value should be sign-extended to the extent required by the target’s ABI (which is usually 32-bits) by the caller (for a parameter) or the callee (for a return value).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates to the code generator that the parameter or return value has the high bits undefined, as for a struct in a register, and therefore does not need to be sign or zero extended.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is the same as default behavior and is only actually used (by some targets) to validate that one of the attributes is always present.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Use of this attribute is target-specific.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the pointer parameter should really be passed by value to the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The attribute implies that a hidden copy of the pointee is made between the caller and the callee, so the callee is unable to modify the value in the caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute is only valid on LLVM pointer arguments.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] It is generally used to pass structs and arrays by value, but is also valid on pointers to scalars.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The copy is considered to belong to the caller not the callee (for example, `readonly` functions should not write to `byval` parameters).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is not a valid attribute for return values.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The byval type argument is only used for its allocation size and alignment (if there is no explicit align attribute).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] That is, the hidden copy is interpreted as a call to memcpy with the allocation size of the specified type, instead of loading from the pointee and storing back into the copy in the type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] In particular, the padding between field types of a struct type is still copied.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The byval attribute also supports specifying an alignment with the `align` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] It indicates the alignment of the stack slot to form and the known alignment of the pointer specified to the call site.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If the alignment is not specified, then the code generator makes a target-specific assumption.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the pointer parameter should really be passed by value to the function, and that the pointer parameter’s pointee has already been initialized before the call instruction.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The argument must be the value returned by the appropriate llvm.call.preallocated.arg on non `musttail` calls, or the corresponding caller parameter in `musttail` calls, although it is ignored during codegen.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A non `musttail` function call with a `preallocated` attribute in any parameter must have a `"preallocated"` operand bundle.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A `musttail` function call cannot have a `"preallocated"` operand bundle.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The preallocated attribute requires a type argument.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The preallocated attribute also supports specifying an alignment with the `align` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the pointer parameter specifies the address of a structure that is the return value of the function in the source program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This pointer must be guaranteed by the caller to be valid: loads and stores to the structure may be assumed by the callee not to trap and to be properly aligned.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The sret type argument specifies the in-memory type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A function that accepts an `sret` argument must return `void`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the pointer value or vector of pointers has the specified alignment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If applied to a vector of pointers, *all* pointers (elements) have the specified alignment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If the pointer value does not have the specified alignment, poison value is returned or passed instead.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `align` attribute should be combined with the `noundef` attribute to ensure a pointer is aligned, or otherwise the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that `align 1` has no effect on non-byval, non-preallocated arguments.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that this attribute has additional semantics when combined with the `byval` or `preallocated` attribute, which are documented there.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that memory locations accessed via pointer values based on the argument or return value are not also accessed, during the execution of the function, via pointer values not *based* on the argument or return value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This guarantee only holds for memory locations that are *modified*, by any means, during the execution of the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If there are other accesses not based on the argument or return value, the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The attribute on a return value also has additional semantics, as described below.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Both the caller and the callee share the responsibility of ensuring that these requirements are met.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For further details, please see the discussion of the NoAlias response in alias analysis.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that this definition of `noalias` is intentionally similar to the definition of `restrict` in C99 for function arguments.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For function return values, C99’s `restrict` is not meaningful, while LLVM’s `noalias` is.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Furthermore, the semantics of the `noalias` attribute on return values are stronger than the semantics of the attribute when used on function arguments.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] On function return values, the `noalias` attribute indicates that the function acts like a system memory allocation function, returning a pointer to allocated storage disjoint from the storage for any other object accessible to the caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute restricts the ways in which the callee may capture the pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute applies only to the particular copy of the pointer passed in this argument.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Additionally, it is possible to specify that some components are only captured in certain locations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Currently only the return value (`ret`) and other (default) locations are supported.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The pointer capture section discusses these semantics in more detail.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that a pointer based on this argument cannot be freed during the execution of the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This includes frees of the pointer on other threads if the free *happens-before* the function return.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Notably, it is still possible to free the underlying object through a pointer that is not based on the argument.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the pointer parameter can be excised using the trampoline intrinsics.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is not a valid attribute for return values and can only be applied to one parameter.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the function always returns the argument as its return value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is a hint to the optimizer and code generator used when generating the caller, allowing value propagation, tail call optimization, and omission of register saves and restores in some cases; it is not checked or enforced when generating the callee.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The parameter and the function return type must be valid operands for the bitcast instruction.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the parameter or return pointer is not null.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute may only be applied to pointer-typed parameters.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is not checked or enforced by LLVM; if the parameter or return pointer is null, poison value is returned or passed instead.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `nonnull` attribute only refers to the address bits of the pointers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If all the address bits are zero, the result will be a poison value, even if the pointer has non-zero non-address bits or non-zero external state.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `nonnull` attribute should be combined with the `noundef` attribute to ensure a pointer is not null or otherwise the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the parameter or return pointer is dereferenceable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A pointer that is dereferenceable can be loaded from speculatively without a risk of trapping.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The number of bytes known to be dereferenceable must be provided in parentheses.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `nonnull` attribute does not imply dereferenceability (consider a pointer to one element past the end of an array), however `dereferenceable(<n>)` does imply `nonnull` in `addrspace(0)` (which is the default address space), except if the `null_pointer_is_valid` function attribute is present.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The pointer should be well defined, otherwise it is undefined behavior.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This means `dereferenceable(<n>)` implies `noundef`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the parameter or return value isn’t both non-null and non-dereferenceable (up to `<n>` bytes) at the same time.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] All non-null pointers tagged with `dereferenceable_or_null(<n>)` are `dereferenceable(<n>)`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the parameter is the self/context parameter.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the parameter is the asynchronous context parameter and triggers the creation of a target-specific extended frame record to store this pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute is motivated to model and optimize Swift error handling.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] It can be applied to a parameter with pointer-to-pointer type or a pointer-sized alloca.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] At the call site, the actual argument that corresponds to a `swifterror` parameter has to come from a `swifterror` alloca or the `swifterror` parameter of the caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A `swifterror` value (either the parameter or the alloca) can only be loaded and stored from, or used as a `swifterror` argument.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] These constraints allow the calling convention to optimize access to `swifterror` variables by associating them with a specific register at call boundaries rather than placing them in memory.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Since this does change the calling convention, a function which uses the `swifterror` attribute on a parameter is not ABI-compatible with one which does not.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] These constraints also allow LLVM to assume that a `swifterror` argument does not alias any other memory visible within a function and that a `swifterror` alloca passed as an argument does not escape.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates the parameter is required to be an immediate value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This must be a trivial immediate integer or floating-point constant.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Undef or constant expressions are not valid.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is only valid on intrinsic declarations and cannot be applied to a call site or arbitrary function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute applies to parameters and return values.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If the value representation contains any undefined or poison bits, the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that this does not refer to padding introduced by the type’s storage representation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If memory sanitizer is enabled, `noundef` becomes an ABI attribute and must match between the call-site and the function definition.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute applies to parameters and return values with floating-point and vector of floating-point types, as well as supported aggregates of such types (matching the supported types for fast-math flags).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The test mask has the same format as the second argument to the llvm.is.fpclass, and indicates which classes of floating-point values are not permitted for the value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For example, a bitmask of 3 indicates the parameter may not be a NaN.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If the value is a floating-point class indicated by the `nofpclass` test mask, a poison value is passed or returned instead.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates the alignment that should be considered by the backend when assigning this parameter or return value to a stack slot during calling convention lowering.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The enforcement of the specified alignment is target-dependent, as target-specific calling convention rules may override this value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute serves the purpose of carrying language-specific alignment information that is not mapped to base types in the backend (for example, over-alignment specification through language attributes).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The function parameter marked with this attribute is the alignment in bytes of the newly allocated block returned by this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The returned value must either have the specified alignment or be the null pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The return value MAY be more aligned than the requested alignment, but not less aligned.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Invalid (e.g., non-power-of-2) alignments are permitted for the allocalign parameter, so long as the returned pointer is null.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute may only be applied to integer parameters.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The function parameter marked with this attribute is the pointer that will be manipulated by the allocator.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For a realloc-like function the pointer will be invalidated upon success (but the same address may be returned), for a free-like function the pointer will always be invalidated.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that the function does not dereference that pointer argument, even though it may read or write the memory that the pointer points to if accessed through other pointers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If a function reads from or writes to a readnone pointer argument, the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that the function does not write through this pointer argument, even though it may write to the memory that the pointer points to.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If a function writes to a readonly pointer argument, the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that the function may write to, but does not read through this pointer argument (even though it may read from the memory that the pointer points to).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute is understood in the same way as the `memory(write)` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] That is, the pointer may still be read as long as the read is not observable outside the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] See the `memory` documentation for precise semantics.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute is only meaningful in conjunction with `dereferenceable(N)` or another attribute that implies the first `N` bytes of the pointer argument are dereferenceable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] In that case, the attribute indicates that the first `N` bytes will be (non-atomically) loaded and stored back on entry to the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This implies that it’s possible to introduce spurious stores on entry to the function without introducing traps or data races.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This does not necessarily hold throughout the whole function, as the pointer may escape to a different thread during the execution of the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The “other attributes” that imply dereferenceability are `dereferenceable_or_null` (if the pointer is non-null) and the `sret`, `byval`, `byref`, `inalloca`, `preallocated` family of attributes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that not all of these combinations are useful, e.g.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] `byval` arguments are known to be writable even without this attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `writable` attribute cannot be combined with `readnone`, `readonly` or a `memory` attribute that does not contain `argmem: write`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that the function initializes the ranges of the pointer parameter’s memory `[%p+LoN, %p+HiN)`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Colloquially, this means that all bytes in the specified range are written before the function returns, and not read prior to the initializing write.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If the function unwinds, the write may not happen.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Formally, this is specified in terms of an “initialized” shadow state for all bytes in the range, which is set to “not initialized” at function entry.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Additionally, if the function returns normally, write an undef value to all bytes that are part of the range and have not been marked as “initialized”.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute only holds for the memory accessed via this pointer parameter.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Other arbitrary accesses to the same memory via other pointers are allowed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `writable` or `dereferenceable` attribute do not imply the `initializes` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `initializes` attribute does not imply `writeonly` since `initializes` allows reading from the pointer after writing.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute is a list of constant ranges in ascending order with no overlapping or consecutive list elements.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] `LoN/HiN` are 64-bit integers, and negative values are allowed in case the argument points partway into an allocation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] On a `byval` argument, `initializes` refers to the given parts of the callee copy being overwritten.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A `byval` callee can never initialize the original caller memory passed to the `byval` argument.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] At a high level, this attribute indicates that the pointer argument is dead if the call unwinds, in the sense that the caller will not depend on the contents of the memory.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Stores that would only be visible on the unwind path can be elided.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] More precisely, the behavior is as-if any memory written through the pointer during the execution of the function is overwritten with a poison value on unwind.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This includes memory written by the implicit write implied by the `writable` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The caller is allowed to access the affected memory, but all loads that are not preceded by a store will return poison.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute cannot be applied to return values.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that the memory pointed to by the argument is dead upon function return, both upon normal return and if the calls unwinds, meaning that the caller will not depend on its contents.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Stores that would be observable either on the return path or on the unwind path may be elided.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A number of bytes known to be dead may optionally be provided in parentheses.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If a number of bytes is not specified, all memory reachable through the pointer is marked as dead on return.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Specifically, the behavior is as-if any memory written through the pointer during the execution of the function is overwritten with a poison value upon function return.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The caller may access the memory, but any load not preceded by a store will return poison.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If a byte count is specified, only writes within the specified range are overwritten with poison on function return.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute does not imply aliasing properties.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For pointer arguments that do not alias other memory locations, `noalias` attribute may be used in conjunction.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Conversely, this attribute always implies `dead_on_unwind`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] When a byte count is specified, `dead_on_unwind` is implied only for that range.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute expresses the possible range of the parameter or return value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If the value is not in the specified range, it is converted to poison.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute may only be applied to parameters or return values with integer or vector of integer types.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For vector-typed parameters, the range is applied element-wise.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The supported values of *name* include those built in to LLVM and any provided by loaded plugins.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Specifying a GC strategy will cause the compiler to alter its output in order to support the named garbage collection algorithm.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Note that LLVM itself does not contain a garbage collector, this functionality is restricted to generating machine code which can interoperate with a collector provided externally.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Prefix data is data associated with a function which the code generator will emit immediately before the function’s entrypoint.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The purpose of this feature is to allow frontends to associate language-specific runtime metadata with specific functions and make it available through the function pointer while still allowing the function pointer to be called.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] To access the data for a given function, a program may bitcast the function pointer to a pointer to the constant’s type and dereference index -1.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This implies that the IR symbol points just past the end of the prefix data.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Prefix data is laid out as if it were an initializer for a global variable of the prefix data’s type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The function will be placed such that the beginning of the prefix data is aligned.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This means that if the size of the prefix data is not a multiple of the alignment size, the function’s entrypoint will not be aligned.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If alignment of the function’s entrypoint is desired, padding must be added to the prefix data.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A function may have prefix data but no body.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This has similar semantics to the `available_externally` linkage in that the data may be used by the optimizers but will not be emitted in the object file.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `prologue` attribute allows arbitrary code (encoded as bytes) to be inserted prior to the function body.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This can be used for enabling function hot-patching and instrumentation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] To maintain the semantics of ordinary function calls, the prologue data must have a particular format.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Specifically, it must begin with a sequence of bytes which decode to a sequence of machine instructions, valid for the module’s target, which transfer control to the point immediately succeeding the prologue data, without performing any other visible action.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This allows the inliner and other passes to reason about the semantics of the function definition without needing to reason about the prologue data.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Obviously this makes the format of the prologue data highly target dependent.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A function may have prologue data but no body.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The `personality` attribute permits functions to specify what function to use for exception handling.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Attribute groups are groups of attributes that are referenced by objects within the IR.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] They are important for keeping `.ll` files readable, because a lot of functions will use the same set of attributes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] In the degenerate case of a `.ll` file that corresponds to a single `.c` file, the single attribute group will capture the important command line flags used to build that file.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] An attribute group is a module-level object.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] To use an attribute group, an object references the attribute group’s ID (e.g., `#37`).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] An object may refer to more than one attribute group.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] In that situation, the attributes from the different groups are merged.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Function attributes are set to communicate additional information about a function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Function attributes are considered to be part of the function, not of the function type, so functions with different function attributes can have the same function type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Function attributes are simple keywords or strings that follow the specified type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Multiple attributes, when required, are separated by spaces.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that, when emitting the prologue and epilogue, the backend should forcibly align the stack pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Specify the desired alignment, which must be a power of two, in parentheses.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates which “family” an allocator function is part of.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] To avoid collisions, the family name should match the mangled name of the primary allocator function, that is “malloc” for malloc/calloc/realloc/free, “_Znwm” for `::operator::new` and `::operator::delete`, and “_ZnwmSt11align_val_t” for aligned `::operator::new` and `::operator::delete`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Matching malloc/realloc/free calls within a family can be optimized, but mismatched ones will be left alone.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Describes the behavior of an allocation function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The first three options are mutually exclusive, and the remaining options describe more details of how the function behaves.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The remaining options are invalid for “free”-type functions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Calls to functions annotated with `allockind` are subject to allocation elision: Calls to allocator functions can be removed, and the allocation served from a “virtual” allocator instead.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Notably, this is allowed even if the allocator calls have side-effects.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] In other words, for each allocation there is a non-deterministic choice between calling the allocator as usual, or using a virtual, side-effect-free allocator instead.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If multiple allocation functions operate on the same allocation, allocation elision is only allowed for pairs of “alloc” and “free” with the same `"alloc-family"` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For this purpose, a “realloc” call may be decomposed into “alloc” and “free” operations, as long as at least one of them will be elided.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that another function is equivalent to an allocator function, but returns zeroed memory.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The function must have “zeroed” allocation behavior, the same `alloc-family`, and take exactly the same arguments.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that the annotated function will always return at least a given number of bytes (or null).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Its arguments are zero-indexed parameter numbers; if one argument is provided, then it’s assumed that at least `CallSite.Args[EltSizeParam]` bytes will be available at the returned pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] If two are provided, then it’s assumed that `CallSite.Args[EltSizeParam] * CallSite.Args[NumEltsParam]` bytes are available.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The referenced parameters must be integer types.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] No assumptions are made about the contents of the returned block of memory.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that the inliner should attempt to inline this function into callers whenever possible, ignoring any active inlining size threshold for this caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This indicates that the callee function at a call site should be recognized as a built-in function, even though the function’s declaration uses the `nobuiltin` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is only valid at call sites for direct calls to functions that are declared with the `nobuiltin` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that this function is rarely called.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] When computing edge weights, basic blocks post-dominated by a cold function call are also considered to be cold and, thus, given a low weight.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that this function is convergent.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] When it appears on a call/invoke, the convergent attribute indicates that we should treat the call as though we’re calling a convergent function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This is particularly useful on indirect calls; without this we may treat such calls as though the target is non-convergent.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] See Convergent Operation Semantics for further details.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] It is an error to call llvm.experimental.convergence.entry from a function that does not have this attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] When instrumenting code with sanitizers, it can be important to skip certain functions to ensure no instrumentation is applied to them.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute is not always similar to absent `sanitize_<name>` attributes: depending on the specific sanitizer, code can be inserted into functions regardless of the `sanitize_<name>` attribute to prevent false positive reports.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] `disable_sanitizer_instrumentation` disables all kinds of instrumentation, taking precedence over the `sanitize_<name>` attributes and other compiler flags.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute denotes that an error diagnostic should be emitted when a call of a function with this attribute is not eliminated via optimization.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] Front ends can provide optional `srcloc` metadata nodes on call sites of such callees to attach information about where in the source language such a call came from.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] A string value can be provided as a note.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute denotes that a warning diagnostic should be emitted when a call of a function with this attribute is not eliminated via optimization.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute tells the code generator that returns from functions should be replaced with jumps to externally-defined architecture-specific symbols.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] For X86, this symbol’s identifier is `__x86_return_thunk`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute tells the code generator whether the function should keep the frame pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The code generator may emit the frame pointer even if this attribute says the frame pointer can be eliminated.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that this function is a hot spot of the program execution.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] The function will be optimized more aggressively and will be placed into a special subsection of the text section to improve locality.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] When profile feedback is enabled, this attribute takes precedence over the profile information.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] By marking a function `hot`, users can work around the cases where the training input does not have good coverage on all the hot functions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] This attribute indicates that the source code contained a hint that inlining this function is desirable (such as the “inline” keyword in C/C++).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p02] It is just a hint; it imposes no requirements on the inliner.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the function should be added to a jump-instruction table at code-generation time, and that all address-taken references to this function should be replaced with a reference to the appropriate jump-instruction-table function pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Note that this creates a new pointer for the original function, which means that code that depends on function-pointer identity can break.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] So, any function annotated with `jumptable` must also be `unnamed_addr`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute specifies the possible memory effects of the call-site or function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It allows specifying the possible access kinds (`none`, `read`, `write`, or `readwrite`) for the possible memory location kinds (`argmem`, `inaccessiblemem`, `errnomem`, `target_mem0`, `target_mem1`, as well as a default).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If the `memory` attribute is not specified, then `memory(readwrite)` is implied (all memory effects are possible).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The memory effects of a call can be computed as `CallSiteEffects & (FunctionEffects | OperandBundleEffects)`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Thus, the call-site annotation takes precedence over the potential effects described by either the function annotation or the operand bundles.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute suggests that optimization passes and code generator passes make choices that keep the code size of this function as small as possible and perform optimizations that may sacrifice runtime performance in order to minimize the size of the generated code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute is incompatible with the `optdebug` and `optnone` attributes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute disables prologue / epilogue emission for the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This can have very system-specific consequences.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The arguments of a `naked` function can not be referenced through IR values.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] When this attribute is set to true, the inliner discards source locations when inlining code and instead uses the source location of the call site.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Breakpoints set on code that was inlined into the current function will not fire during the execution of the inlined call sites.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If the debugger stops inside an inlined call site, it will appear to be stopped at the outermost inlined call site.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] When this attribute is set to true, the jump tables and lookup tables that can be generated from a switch case lowering are disabled.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This indicates that the callee function at a call site is not recognized as a built-in function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] LLVM will retain the original call and not replace it with equivalent code based on the semantics of the built-in function, unless the call site uses the `builtin` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This is valid at call sites and on function declarations and definitions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the function is only allowed to jump back into the caller’s module by a return or an exception, and is not allowed to jump back by invoking a callback function, a direct, possibly transitive, external function call, use of `longjmp`, or other means.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It is a compiler hint that is used at the module level to improve dataflow analysis, dropped during linking, and has no effect on functions defined in the current module.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A call to this function is not a source of divergence.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] In uniformity analysis, a *source of divergence* is an instruction that generates divergence even if its inputs are uniform.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A call with no further information would normally be considered a source of divergence; setting this attribute on a function means that a call to it is not a source of divergence.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that calls to the function cannot be duplicated.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A call to a `noduplicate` function may be moved within its parent function, but may not be duplicated within its parent function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A function containing a `noduplicate` call may still be an inlining candidate, provided that the call is not duplicated by inlining.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] That implies that the function has internal linkage and only has one call site, so the original call is dead after inlining.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates that the function does not free any memory allocation which existed before the call, either through direct calls to a memory-deallocation function like `free`, or through synchronization.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Freeing through synchronization here means that a deallocation *happens-before* the function exit but does not *happens-before* the function entry.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] As a result, pointers that are known to be dereferenceable prior to a call to a function with the `nofree` attribute are still known to be dereferenceable after the call.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A `nofree` function is explicitly allowed to free memory which it allocated or arrange for another thread to free such memory on its behalf.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] As a result, perhaps surprisingly, a `nofree` function can return a pointer to a previously deallocated allocated object.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This inhibits optimizations that use floating-point code and floating-point registers for operations that are not nominally floating-point.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] LLVM instructions that perform floating-point operations or require access to floating-point registers may still cause floating-point code to be generated.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Also inhibits optimizations that create SIMD/vector code and registers from scalar code such as vectorization or memcpy/memset optimization.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Vector instructions present in IR may still cause vector code to be generated.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the inliner should never inline this function in any situation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute may not be used together with the `alwaysinline` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Disables any interprocedural analysis that inspects the definition of this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute is equivalent to moving this function definition to a separate, optimizer-opaque, module.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Any attributes on the function are still respected (as they would be if they remained on a function declaration in this module).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute does *not* control inlining or outlining.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Add the `noinline` and `nooutline` attributes as well in cases where inlining and outlining should additionally be disabled.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that calls to this function should never be merged during optimization.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] For example, it will prevent tail merging otherwise identical code sequences that raise an exception or terminate the program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Tail merging normally reduces the precision of source location information, making stack traces less useful for debugging.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute gives the user control over the tradeoff between code size and debug information precision.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute suppresses lazy symbol binding for the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This may make calls to the function faster, at the cost of extra program startup time if the function is not called during program startup.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute prevents instrumentation-based profiling, used for coverage or profile based optimization, from being added to a function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It also blocks inlining if the caller and callee have different values of this attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute does not restrict inlining, so instrumented instructions could end up in this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the code generator should not use a red zone, even if the target-specific ABI normally permits it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the code generator should not use direct TLS access through segment registers, even if the target-specific ABI normally permits it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates that the function never returns normally, hence through a return instruction.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This produces undefined behavior at runtime if the function ever does dynamically return.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Annotated functions may still raise an exception, i.a., `nounwind` is not implied.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates that the function is not recursive and does not participate in recursion.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This means that the function never occurs inside a cycle in the dynamic call graph.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates that a call of this function will either exhibit undefined behavior or comes back and continues execution at a point in the existing call stack that includes the current invocation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If an invocation of an annotated function does not return control back to a point in the call stack, the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates that the function does not introduce any *synchronizes-with* edges in the sense of the memory model.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] In particular, synchronization is considered possible in the presence of *atomic* accesses that enforce an order, thus not “unordered” and “monotonic”, as well as *convergent* function calls.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Note that *convergent* operations can involve communication that is considered to be not through memory and does not necessarily imply an ordering between threads for the purposes of the memory model.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Therefore, an operation can be both *convergent* and *nosync*.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a *nosync* function does ever synchronize with another thread, the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates that the function never raises an exception.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If the function does raise an exception, its runtime behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] However, functions marked nounwind may still trap or generate asynchronous exceptions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Exception handling schemes that are recognized by LLVM to handle asynchronous exceptions, such as SEH, will still provide their implementation defined semantics.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that bounds checking sanitizer instrumentation is disabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that SanitizerCoverage instrumentation is disabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If `null_pointer_is_valid` is set, then the `null` address in address-space 0 is considered to be a valid address for memory loads and stores.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Any analysis or optimization should not treat dereferencing a pointer to `null` as undefined behavior in this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Note: Comparing the address of a global variable to `null` may still evaluate to false because of a limitation in querying this attribute inside constant expressions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute suggests that optimization passes and code generator passes should make choices that try to preserve debug info without significantly degrading runtime performance.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute is incompatible with the `minsize`, `optsize`, and `optnone` attributes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that this function should be optimized for maximum fuzzing signal.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates that most optimization passes will skip this function, with the exception of interprocedural optimization passes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Code generation defaults to the “fast” instruction selector.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute cannot be used together with the `alwaysinline` attribute; this attribute is also incompatible with the `minsize`, `optsize`, and `optdebug` attributes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute requires the `noinline` attribute to be specified on the function as well, so the function is never inlined into any caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Only functions with the `alwaysinline` attribute are valid candidates for inlining into the body of this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute suggests that optimization passes and code generator passes make choices that keep the code size of this function low, and otherwise do optimizations specifically to reduce code size as long as they do not significantly impact runtime performance.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute tells the code generator that the code generated for this function needs to follow certain conventions that make it possible for a runtime function to patch over it later.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute by itself does not imply restrictions on inter-procedural optimizations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] All of the semantic effects the patching may have to be separately conveyed via the linkage type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute specifies the number of target-specific NOP instructions emitted before the function entry label.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute specifies the number of target-specific NOP instructions emitted after the function entry label.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] These NOPs are emitted before the function prologue.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute specifies the section used to record the start of the patchable function entry area when such a section is emitted.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If omitted, the default section name is `__patchable_function_entries`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the function will trigger a guard region in the end of the stack.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It ensures that accesses to the stack must be no further apart than the size of the guard region to a previous access of the stack.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It takes one required string value, the name of the stack probing function that will be called.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function that has a `"probe-stack"` attribute is inlined into a function with another `"probe-stack"` attribute, the resulting function has the `"probe-stack"` attribute of the caller.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function that has a `"probe-stack"` attribute is inlined into a function that has no `"probe-stack"` attribute at all, the resulting function has the `"probe-stack"` attribute of the callee.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute controls the behavior of stack probes: either the `"probe-stack"` attribute, or ABI-required stack probes, if any.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It defines the size of the guard region.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It ensures that if the function may use more stack space than the size of the guard region, a stack probing sequence will be emitted.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It takes one required integer value, which is 4096 by default.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function that has a `"stack-probe-size"` attribute is inlined into a function with another `"stack-probe-size"` attribute, the resulting function has the `"stack-probe-size"` attribute that has the lower numeric value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function that has a `"stack-probe-size"` attribute is inlined into a function that has no `"stack-probe-size"` attribute at all, the resulting function has the `"stack-probe-size"` attribute of the callee.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute disables ABI-required stack probes, if any.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that this function can return twice.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The C `setjmp` is an example of such a function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The compiler disables some optimizations (like tail calls) in the caller of these functions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that SafeStack protection is enabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function that has a `safestack` attribute is inlined into a function that doesn’t have a `safestack` attribute or which has an `ssp`, `sspstrong` or `sspreq` attribute, then the resulting function will have a `safestack` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that AddressSanitizer checks (dynamic address safety analysis) are enabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that MemorySanitizer checks (dynamic detection of accesses to uninitialized memory) are enabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that ThreadSanitizer checks (dynamic thread safety analysis) are enabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that HWAddressSanitizer checks (dynamic address safety analysis based on tagged pointers) are enabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that MemTagSanitizer checks (dynamic address safety analysis based on Armv8 MTE) are enabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that RealtimeSanitizer checks (realtime safety analysis - no allocations, syscalls or exceptions) are enabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that RealtimeSanitizer should error immediately if the attributed function is called during invocation of a function attributed with `sanitize_realtime`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute is incompatible with the `sanitize_realtime` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that implicit allocation token instrumentation is enabled for this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that Speculative Load Hardening should be enabled for the function body.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Speculative Load Hardening is a best-effort mitigation against information leak attacks that make use of control flow miss-speculation - specifically miss-speculation of whether a branch is taken or not.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Typically vulnerabilities enabling such attacks are classified as “Spectre variant #1”.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Notably, this does not attempt to mitigate against miss-speculation of branch target, classified as “Spectre variant #2” vulnerabilities.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Inlining a function that carries this attribute will cause the caller to gain the attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This is intended to provide a maximally conservative model where the code in a function annotated with this attribute will always (even after inlining) end up hardened.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates that the function does not have any effects besides calculating its result and does not have undefined behavior.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Note that `speculatable` is not enough to conclude that along any particular execution path the number of calls to this function will not be externally observable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute is only valid on functions and declarations, not on individual call sites.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function is incorrectly marked as speculatable and really does exhibit undefined behavior, the undefined behavior may be observed even if the call site is dead code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the function should emit a stack smashing protector.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It is in the form of a “canary” — a random value placed on the stack before the local variables that’s checked upon return from the function to see if it has been overwritten.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A heuristic is used to determine if a function needs stack protectors or not.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Variables that are identified as requiring a protector will be arranged on the stack such that they are adjacent to the stack protector guard.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function with an `ssp` attribute is inlined into a calling function, the attribute is not carried over to the calling function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute causes a strong heuristic to be used when determining if a function needs stack protectors.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Small arrays and structures containing small arrays (`< ssp-buffer-size`) are 2nd closest to the protector.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Variables that have had their address taken are 3rd closest to the protector.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This overrides the `ssp` function attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function with an `sspstrong` attribute is inlined into a calling function which has an `ssp` attribute, the calling function’s attribute will be upgraded to `sspstrong`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the function should *always* emit a stack smashing protector.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This overrides the `ssp` and `sspstrong` function attributes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a function with an `sspreq` attribute is inlined into a calling function which has an `ssp` or `sspstrong` attribute, the calling function’s attribute will be upgraded to `sspreq`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the function was called from a scope that requires strict floating-point semantics.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] LLVM will not attempt any optimizations that require assumptions about the floating-point rounding mode or that might alter the state of floating-point status flags that might otherwise be set or cleared by calling this function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] LLVM will not introduce any new floating-point instructions that may trap.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This indicates the denormal (subnormal) handling that may be assumed for the default floating-point environment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The elements may be one of `ieee`, `preservesign`, `positivezero`, or `dynamic`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The first entry indicates the flushing mode for the result of floating point operations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The second indicates the handling of denormal inputs to floating point instructions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] For compatibility with older bitcode, if the second value is omitted, both input and output modes will assume the same mode.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If this is attribute is not specified, the default is `ieee|ieee`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If the output mode is `preservesign`, or `positivezero`, denormal outputs may be flushed to zero by standard floating-point operations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It is not mandated that flushing to zero occurs, but if a denormal output is flushed to zero, it must respect the sign mode.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If the mode is `dynamic`, the behavior is derived from the dynamic state of the floating-point environment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Transformations which depend on the behavior of denormal values should not be performed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] While this indicates the expected floating point mode the function will be executed with, this does not make any attempt to ensure the mode is consistent.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] User or platform code is expected to set the floating point mode appropriately before function entry.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This may optionally specify a second pair, prefixed with `float:`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This provides an override for the behavior of 32-bit float type (or vectors of 32-bit floats).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If the input mode is `preservesign`, or `positivezero`, a floating-point operation must treat any input denormal value as zero.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] In some situations, if an instruction does not respect this mode, the input may need to be converted to 0 as if by `@llvm.canonicalize` during lowering for correctness.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This provides an override for the behavior of 32-bit float type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If this is present, this overrides the base handling of the default mode.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Not all targets support separately setting the denormal mode per type, and no attempt is made to diagnose unsupported uses.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Currently this attribute is respected by the AMDGPU and NVPTX backends.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the function will delegate to some other function with a tail call.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The prototype of a thunk should not be used for optimization purposes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The caller is expected to cast the thunk prototype to match the thunk target prototype.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the ABI being targeted requires that an unwind table entry be produced for this function even if we can show that no exceptions pass by it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This is normally the case for the ELF x86-64 abi, but it can be disabled for some compilation units.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The optional parameter describes what kind of unwind tables to generate: `sync` for normal unwind tables, `async` for asynchronous (instruction precise) unwind tables.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Without the parameter, the attribute `uwtable` is equivalent to `uwtable(async)`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that no control-flow check will be performed on the attributed entity.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It disables -fcf-protection=<> for a specific entity to fine grain the HW control flow protection mechanism.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The flag is target independent and currently appertains to a function or function pointer.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the ShadowCallStack checks are enabled for the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The instrumentation checks that the return address for the function has not changed between the function prologue and epilogue.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the function is required to return, unwind, or interact with the environment in an observable way e.g., via a volatile memory access, I/O, or other synchronization.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The `mustprogress` attribute is intended to model the requirements of the first section of [intro.progress] of the C++ Standard.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] As a consequence, a loop in a function with the `mustprogress` attribute can be assumed to terminate if it does not interact with the environment in an observable way, and terminating loops without side-effects can be removed.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a `mustprogress` function does not satisfy this contract, the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If a `mustprogress` function calls a function not marked `mustprogress`, and that function never returns, the program is well-defined even if there isn’t any other observable progress.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Note that `willreturn` implies `mustprogress`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute sets a threshold to emit diagnostics once the frame size is known should the frame size exceed the specified value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It takes one required integer value, which should be a non-negative integer, and less than *UINT_MAX*.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It’s unspecified which threshold will be used when duplicate definitions are linked together with differing values.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This function attribute indicates *vscale* is a power-of-two within a specified range.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] *min* must be a power-of-two that is greater than 0.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] When specified, *max* must be a power-of-two greater-than-or-equal to *min* or 0 to signify an unbounded maximum.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The syntax *vscale_range(<val>)* can be used to set both *min* and *max* to the same value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Functions that don’t include this attribute make no assumptions about the range of *vscale*.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that outlining passes should not modify the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the result of the function (prior to application of return attributes/metadata) will not be undef or poison if all arguments are not undef and not poison.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the implementation is modular on a particular format string argument.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If the compiler can determine that not all aspects of the implementation are needed, it can report which aspects were needed and redirect the call to a modular implementation function instead.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The compiler reports that an implementation aspect is needed by issuing a relocation for the symbol *<impl_name>_<aspect>`*.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This arranges for code and data needed to support the aspect of the implementation to be brought into the link to satisfy weak references in the modular implemenation function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The first three arguments have the same semantics as the arguments to the C `format` attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute can be attached to a call to list the vector functions associated to the function.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Notice that the attribute cannot be attached to a invoke or a callbr instruction.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The attribute consists of a comma separated list of mangled names.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The order of the list does not imply preference (it is logically a set).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The compiler is free to pick any listed vector function of its choosing.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] When present, the attribute informs the compiler that the function `<scalar_name>` has a corresponding vector variant that can be used to perform the concurrent invocation of `<scalar_name>` on vectors.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The shape of the vector function is described by the tokens between the prefix `_ZGV` and the `<scalar_name>` token.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The standard name of the vector function is `_ZGV<isa><mask><vlen><parameters>_<scalar_name>`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] When present, the optional token `(<vector_redirection>)` informs the compiler that a custom name is provided in addition to the standard one (custom names can be provided for example via the use of `declare variant` in OpenMP 5.0).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The declaration of the variant must be present in the IR Module.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The signature of the vector variant is determined by the rules of the Vector Function ABI (VFABI) specifications of the target.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] For Arm and X86, the VFABI can be found at https://github.com/ARM-software/abi-aa and https://software.intel.com/content/www/us/en/develop/download/vector-simd-function-abi.html, respectively.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] For X86 and Arm targets, the values of the tokens in the standard name are those that are defined in the VFABI.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] LLVM has an internal `<isa>` token that can be used to create scalar-to-vector mappings for functions that are not directly associated to any of the target ISAs (for example, some of the mappings stored in the TargetLibraryInfo).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute is required on calls to `llvm.call.preallocated.arg` and cannot be used on any other call.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] See llvm.call.preallocated.arg for more details.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Attributes may be set to communicate additional information about a global variable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Unlike function attributes, attributes on a global variable are grouped into a single attribute group.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the global variable should not have AddressSanitizer instrumentation applied to it, because it was annotated with *__attribute__((no_sanitize(“address”)))*, *__attribute__((disable_sanitizer_instrumentation))*, or included in the *-fsanitize-ignorelist* file.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the global variable should not have HWAddressSanitizer instrumentation applied to it, because it was annotated with *__attribute__((no_sanitize(“hwaddress”)))*, *__attribute__((disable_sanitizer_instrumentation))*, or included in the *-fsanitize-ignorelist* file.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the global variable should have AArch64 memory tags (MTE) instrumentation applied to it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute causes the suppression of certain optimizations, like GlobalMerge, as well as ensuring extra directives are emitted in the assembly and extra bits of metadata are placed in the object file so that the linker can ensure the accesses are protected by MTE.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute is added by clang when *-fsanitize=memtag-globals* is provided, as long as the global is not marked with *__attribute__((no_sanitize(“memtag”)))*, *__attribute__((disable_sanitizer_instrumentation))*, or included in the *-fsanitize-ignorelist* file.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The AArch64 Globals Tagging pass may remove this attribute when it’s not possible to tag the global (e.g., it’s a TLS variable).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute indicates that the global variable, when instrumented with AddressSanitizer, should be checked for ODR violations.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This attribute is applied to global variables that are dynamically initialized according to C++ rules.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Operand bundles are tagged sets of SSA values or metadata strings that can be associated with certain LLVM instructions (currently only `call` s and `invoke` s).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] In a way they are like metadata, but dropping them is incorrect and will change program semantics.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Operand bundles are **not** part of a function’s signature, and a given function may be called from multiple places with different kinds of operand bundles.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This reflects the fact that the operand bundles are conceptually a part of the `call` (or `invoke`), not the callee being dispatched to.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Operand bundles are a generic mechanism intended to support runtime-introspection-like functionality for managed languages.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] While the exact semantics of an operand bundle depend on the bundle tag, there are certain limitations to how much the presence of an operand bundle can influence the semantics of a program.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] These restrictions are described as the semantics of an “unknown” operand bundle.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] As long as the behavior of an operand bundle is describable within these restrictions, LLVM does not need to have special knowledge of the operand bundle to not miscompile programs containing it.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] More specific types of operand bundles are described below.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Deoptimization operand bundles are characterized by the `"deopt"` operand bundle tag.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] These operand bundles represent an alternate “safe” continuation for the call site they’re attached to, and can be used by a suitable runtime to deoptimize the compiled frame at the specified call site.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] There can be at most one `"deopt"` operand bundle attached to a call site.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Exact details of deoptimization are out of scope for the language reference, but it usually involves rewriting a compiled frame into a set of interpreted frames.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] From the compiler’s perspective, deoptimization operand bundles make the call sites they’re attached to at least `readonly`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] They read through all of their pointer typed operands (even if they’re not otherwise escaped) and the entire visible heap.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Deoptimization operand bundles do not capture their operands except during deoptimization, in which case control will not be returned to the compiled frame.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The inliner knows how to inline through calls that have deoptimization operand bundles.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Just like inlining through a normal call site involves composing the normal and exceptional continuations, inlining through a call site with a deoptimization operand bundle needs to appropriately compose the “safe” deoptimization continuation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The inliner does this by prepending the parent’s deoptimization continuation to every deoptimization continuation in the inlined body.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Funclet operand bundles are characterized by the `"funclet"` operand bundle tag.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] These operand bundles indicate that a call site is within a particular funclet.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] There can be at most one `"funclet"` operand bundle attached to a call site and it must have exactly one bundle operand.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Similarly, if no funclet EH pads have been entered-but-not-yet-exited, executing a `call` or `invoke` with a `"funclet"` bundle is undefined behavior.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] GC transition operand bundles are characterized by the `"gc-transition"` operand bundle tag.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] These operand bundles mark a call as a transition between a function with one GC strategy to a function with a different GC strategy.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If coordinating the transition between GC strategies requires additional code generation at the call site, these bundles may contain any values that are needed by the generated code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The bundle contains an arbitrary list of Values which need to be passed to GC transition code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] They will be lowered and passed as operands to the appropriate `GC_TRANSITION` nodes in the selection DAG.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] It is assumed that these arguments must be available before and after (but not necessarily during) the execution of the callee.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Operand bundles on an llvm.assume allow representing assumptions that hold at the location of the assume.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Operand bundles enable assumptions that are either hard or impossible to represent as a boolean argument of an llvm.assume.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Assumes with operand bundles must have `i1 true` as the condition operand.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Just like for the argument of llvm.assume, if any of the provided guarantees are violated at runtime the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Equivalent to align(%align) on `%p`, or `%p - %offset` if the `%offset` argument exists, except that `%align` may be a non-power-of-two alignment (including a zero alignment).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] If `%align` is not a power of two the pointer value must be all-zero.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Equivalent to dereferenceable(%size) on `%p`, except that `%size` may also be zero, in which case the bundle doesn’t imply `nonnull`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Equivalent to dereferenceable_or_null(%size) on `%p`, except that `%size` may also be zero.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This is used to drop an assume where the `llvm.assume` call cannot be replaced or dropped.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This indicates that no pointer based on one of its arguments can alias any pointer based on the other.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] allows the optimizer to assume that at location of call to llvm.assume `%val` has an alignment of at least 8.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] allows the optimizer to assume that the llvm.assume call location is cold and that `%val` may not be null.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] Preallocated operand bundles are characterized by the `"preallocated"` operand bundle tag.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] These operand bundles allow separation of the allocation of the call argument memory from the call site.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] This is necessary to pass non-trivially copyable objects by value in a way that is compatible with MSVC on some targets.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] There can be at most one `"preallocated"` operand bundle attached to a call site and it must have exactly one bundle operand, which is a token generated by `@llvm.call.preallocated.setup`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A call with this operand bundle should not adjust the stack before entering the function, as that will have been done by one of the `@llvm.call.preallocated.*` intrinsics.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A “gc-live” operand bundle is only valid on a gc.statepoint intrinsic.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The operand bundle must contain every pointer to a garbage collected object which potentially needs to be updated by the garbage collector.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] When lowered, any relocated value will be recorded in the corresponding stackmap entry.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] See the intrinsic description for further details.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] A `"clang.arc.attachedcall"` operand bundle on a call indicates the call is implicitly followed by a marker instruction and a call to an ObjC runtime function that uses the result of the call.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The operand bundle takes a mandatory pointer to the runtime function (`@objc_retainAutoreleasedReturnValue` or `@objc_unsafeClaimAutoreleasedReturnValue`).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p03] The return value of a call with this bundle is used by a call to `@llvm.objc.clang.arc.noop.use` unless the called function’s return type is void, in which case the operand bundle is ignored.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The operand bundle is needed to ensure the call is immediately followed by the marker instruction and the ObjC runtime call in the final output.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Pointer Authentication operand bundles are characterized by the `"ptrauth"` operand bundle tag.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] They are described in the Pointer Authentication document.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] A `"kcfi"` operand bundle on an indirect call indicates that the call will be preceded by a runtime type check, which validates that the call target is prefixed with a type identifier that matches the operand bundle attribute.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Clang emits KCFI operand bundles and the necessary metadata with `-fsanitize=kcfi`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] A “convergencectrl” operand bundle is only valid on a `convergent` operation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] When present, the operand bundle must contain exactly one value of token type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] See the Convergent Operation Semantics document for details.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This operand bundle specifies that if the deactivation symbol is defined to a valid value for the target, the marked instruction will return the value of its first argument instead of calling the specified function or intrinsic.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This is achieved with `PATCHINST` relocations on the target instructions (see the AArch64 psABI for details).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Modules may contain “module-level inline asm” blocks, which corresponds to the GCC “file scope inline asm” blocks.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] These blocks are internally concatenated by LLVM and treated as a single unit, but may be separated in the `.ll` file if desired.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The strings can contain any character by escaping non-printable characters.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The escape sequence used is simply “\xx” where “xx” is the two digit hex code for the number.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Note that the assembly string *must* be parseable by LLVM’s integrated assembler (unless it is disabled), even when emitting a `.s` file.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] A module may specify a target-specific data layout string that specifies how data is to be laid out in memory.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The *layout specification* consists of a list of specifications separated by the minus sign character (‘-‘).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Each specification starts with a letter and may include other information after the letter to define some aspect of the data layout.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Specifies that the target lays out data in big-endian form.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] That is, the bits with the most significance have the lowest address location.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Specifies that the target lays out data in little-endian form.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] That is, the bits with the least significance have the lowest address location.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Specifies the natural alignment of the stack in bits.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Alignment promotion of stack variables is limited to the natural stack alignment to avoid dynamic stack realignment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If omitted, the natural stack alignment defaults to “unspecified”, which does not prevent any alignment promotions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Specifies the address space that corresponds to program memory.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Harvard architectures can use this to specify what space LLVM should place things such as functions into.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If omitted, the program memory space defaults to the default address space of 0, which corresponds to a Von Neumann architecture that has code and data in the same space.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Specifies the address space to be used by default when creating global variables.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If omitted, the globals address space defaults to the default address space 0.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Note: variable declarations without an address space are always created in address space 0, this property only affects the default value to be used when creating globals without additional contextual information (e.g., in LLVM passes).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Specifies the address space of objects created by ‘`alloca`’.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Defaults to the default address space of 0.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This specifies the properties of a pointer in address space `as`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The `<size>` parameter specifies the size of the bitwise representation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] For non-integral pointers the representation size may be larger than the address width of the underlying address space (e.g., to accommodate additional metadata).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The alignment requirements are specified via the `<abi>` and `<pref>`erred alignments parameters.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The fourth parameter `<idx>` is the size of the index that used for address calculations such as getelementptr.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] It must be less than or equal to the pointer size.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If not specified, the default index size is equal to the pointer size.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The index size also specifies the width of addresses in this address space.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The address space, `<as>`, is optional, and if not specified, denotes the default address space 0.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The value of `<as>` must be in the range [1,2^24).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The optional `<flags>` are used to specify properties of pointers in this address space: the character `u` marks pointers as having an unstable representation, and `e` marks pointers having external state.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Additionally, the null pointer bit representation can be specified: `z` indicates it is all-zeros, and `o` indicates it is all-ones.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] At most one of `z` or `o` may be specified.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If neither `z` nor `o` is specified, the null pointer bit representation defaults to all-zeros.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The `<name>` is an optional name of that address space, surrounded by `(` and `)`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If the name is specified, it must be unique to that address space and cannot be `A`, `G`, or `P` which are pre-defined names used to denote alloca, global, and program address space respectively.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This specifies the alignment for an integer type of a given bit `<size>`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The value of `<size>` must be in the range [1,2^24).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] For `i8`, the `<abi>` value must equal 8, that is, `i8` must be naturally aligned.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This specifies the alignment for a vector type of a given bit `<size>`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Specifies that vectors are element-aligned by default, rather than having natural alignment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This specifies the alignment for a floating-point type of a given bit `<size>`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Only values of `<size>` that are supported by the target will work.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] 32 (float) and 64 (double) are supported on all targets; 80 or 128 (different flavors of long double) are also supported on some targets.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This specifies the alignment for an object of aggregate type.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] In addition to the usual requirements for alignment values, the value of `<abi>` can also be zero, which means one byte alignment.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This specifies the alignment for function pointers.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If present, specifies that llvm names are mangled in the output.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Symbols prefixed with the mangling escape character `\01` are passed through directly to the assembler without the escape character.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This specifies a set of native integer widths for the target CPU in bits.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Elements of this set are considered to support most general arithmetic operations efficiently.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This marks pointer types with the specified address spaces as unstable.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The `0` address space cannot be specified as non-integral.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] It is only supported for backwards compatibility, the flags of the `p` specifier should be used instead for new code.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] `<abi>` is a lower bound on what is required for a type to be considered aligned.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] `<pref>` allows providing a more optimal alignment that should be used when possible, primarily for `alloca` and the alignment of global variables.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] It is an optional value that must be greater than or equal to `<abi>`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If omitted, the preceding `:` should also be omitted and `<pref>` will be equal to `<abi>`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Unless explicitly stated otherwise, every alignment specification is provided in bits and must be in the range [1,2^16).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The value must be a power of two times the width of a byte (i.e., `align = 8 * 2^N`).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] When constructing the data layout for a given target, LLVM starts with a default set of specifications which are then (possibly) overridden by the specifications in the `datalayout` keyword.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If no match is found, and the type sought is an integer type, then the smallest integer type that is larger than the bitwidth of the sought type is used.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If none of the specifications are larger than the bitwidth then the largest integer type is used.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] For example, given the default specifications above, the i7 type will use the alignment of i8 (next largest) while both i65 and i256 will use the alignment of i64 (largest specified).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The function of the data layout string may not be what you expect.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Notably, this is not a specification from the frontend of what alignment the code generator should use.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Instead, if specified, the target data layout is required to match what the ultimate *code generator* expects.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This string is used by the mid-level optimizers to improve code, and this only works if it matches what the ultimate code generator uses.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] There is no way to generate IR that does not embed this target-specific detail into the IR.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If you don’t specify the string, the default specifications will be used to generate a Data Layout and the optimization phases will operate accordingly and introduce target specificity into the IR with respect to these default specifications.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] A module may specify a target triple string that describes the target host.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The *target triple* string consists of a series of identifiers delimited by the minus sign character (‘-‘).
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This information is passed along to the backend so that it generates code for the proper architecture.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] It’s possible to override this on the command line with the `-mtriple` command-line option.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] An allocated object, memory object, or simply object, is a region of a memory space that is reserved by a memory allocation such as alloca, heap allocation calls, and global variable definitions.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Once it is allocated, the bytes stored in the region can only be read or written through a pointer that is based on the allocation value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If a pointer that is not based on the object tries to read or write to the object, it is undefined behavior.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Allocated objects that are created with operations recognized by LLVM (such as alloca, heap allocation functions marked as such, and global variables) may *not* change their size.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] (`realloc`-style operations do not change the size of an existing allocated object; instead, they create a new allocated object.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Even if the object is at the same location as the old one, old pointers cannot be used to access this new object.) However, allocated objects can also be created by means not recognized by LLVM, e.g., by directly calling `mmap`.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Those allocated objects are allowed to grow to the right (i.e., keeping the same base address, but increasing their size) while maintaining the validity of existing pointers, as long as they always satisfy the properties described above.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Currently, allocated objects are not permitted to grow to the left or to shrink, nor can they have holes.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] A lifetime of an allocated object is a property that decides its accessibility.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Unless stated otherwise, an allocated object is alive since its allocation, and dead after its deallocation.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] It is undefined behavior to access an allocated object that isn’t alive, but operations that don’t dereference it such as getelementptr, ptrtoint and icmp return a valid result.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] This explains code motion of these instructions across operations that impact the object’s lifetime.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] A stack object’s lifetime can be explicitly specified using llvm.lifetime.start and llvm.lifetime.end intrinsic function calls.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] As an exception to the above, loading from a stack object outside its lifetime is not undefined behavior and returns a poison value instead.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Storing to it is still undefined behavior.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Any memory access must be done through a pointer value associated with an address range of the memory access, otherwise the behavior is undefined.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Note that this definition of *“based”* is intentionally similar to the definition of *“based”* in C99, though it is slightly weaker.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] LLVM IR does not associate types with memory.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The result type of a `load` merely indicates the size and alignment of the memory from which to load, as well as the interpretation of the value.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] The first operand type of a `store` similarly only indicates the size and alignment of the store.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Consequently, type-based alias analysis, aka TBAA, aka `-fstrict-aliasing`, is not applicable to general unadorned LLVM IR.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] Metadata may be used to encode additional information which specialized optimization passes may use to implement type-based alias analysis.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] These two cases are discussed in more detail in the following.
[src:llvm-infrastructure/langref-p04] If an argument does not capture the provenance of the pointer, accesses that are based on the argument and are performed after the function returns (or unwinds) cause undefined behavior.
